<HEADLINE> Saudi King Satisfied With Results of GCC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Saudi King Fahd Ibn
Abdul-Aziz expressed content on Monday on the results of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) summit, which was held on November 27-29
in the Saudi capital of Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
Fahd, who chaired the three-day meeting, hailed the efforts
exerted by the GCC leaders aimed at boosting the role of the
regional political and economic bloc to confront common challenges.
</P>
<P>
The king of the GCC heavyweight expressed his satisfaction at
the Saudi cabinet weekly session in the Yamama Palace in Riyadh,
according to reports of the Saudi Press Agency monitored here.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, GCC leaders agreed to form a long-awaited
customs union by March 1, 2005, with common external tariffs
between 5.5 percent to 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The compromised pact is crucial to the GCC's 18-year ambition
to establish a regional common market and for a free trade zone
with one of its key trading partners, the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the leaders of the oil-rich Gulf states - Saudi
Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Bahrain, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates
- which control some 45 percent of the world's oil reserves, also
pledged joint efforts to stabilize the world oil market.
</P>
<P>
After more than one-year lackluster and thanks to the output
curb by the oil producing states, the world oil market has picked
up recently, with the oil price per barrel hit a nine-year high
of over 25 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
