<HEADLINE> Uganda Sets Condition on Pull-out From Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government would
withdraw its troops from the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC) if the issue of the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF), a main
rebel group active in western Uganda, has been properly addressed.
</P>
<P>
Once the rebels surrender, the Ugandan government would pull
out its troops deployed in the third largest African country,
Minister for Security Muruli Mukasa said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Uganda sent troops into the DRC in August 1998, saying that the
troops, now headquartered in DRC's northern town of Kisangani, are
used to ensure the security of the borders.
</P>
<P>
However, the Congolese government has accused Kampala of
backing the rebels fighting to topple President Laurent Kabila, a
charge Uganda has denied.
</P>
<P>
The ADF rebels began operations in western Uganda in January of
1996. They maim, abduct and rob. They are said to often sneak
into Uganda from eastern parts of the DRC to carry out abductions.
</P>
<P>
There is an outcry among some members of Parliament (MPs) for
making peace with the rebel groups within the countries and an
amnesty bill is soon to be passed by the legislature.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government fully supports the efforts made by the
MPs in western Uganda to persuade ADF rebels to come out and
surrender to the central government, Radio Uganda quoted the
minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The rebels would be pardoned if they come out peacefully,
Mukasa added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
