<HEADLINE> Israeli Officials Urge Palestinians to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli government officials
urged on Monday the Palestinians to return to the negotiating
table and to proceed with the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Danny Yatom, national security advisor to Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, told the Israel Radio that the settlement issue could not
be an obstacle hindering the peace talks and this issue can be
settled through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator Yasser Abed Rabbo told reporters
in Ramallah Monday after the inconclusive eighth session of the
final-status talks that the Palestinian side will no longer
negotiate with Israel until it stops Jewish settlements expansion
in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The Monday talks were scheduled to discuss the Palestinian
refugee issue, but the settlement issue has become the hot topic
for the session.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side was angered by Israeli Housing Ministry's
new tenders for building 500 houses in one settlement in the West
Bank, saying such steps taken by the Israeli government were aimed
at destroying the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Yatom tried to defend the tenders, saying that the current
government was implementing the decision made by former government
led by Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Foreign Minister Nawaf Massalha expressed his
regret over the deadlocked peace talks, urging the Palestinian
side to return to the negotiating table as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Nawaf urged Barak, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
U.S. President Bill Clinton to hold a three-way summit to help
break the impasse in the talks, which are expected to result in a
permanent peace deal by next September.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is scheduled to
visit Israel and Palestinian territories on Tuesday for talks with
Barak and Arafat to give the peace process a push.
</P>
<P>
But the Israeli side has lowered its expectation for Albright's
visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
