<HEADLINE> Canadian Army to Outfit Laser Tag for Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian army is set to
outfit troops for training in the country's largest and most
sophisticated game of laser tag, said local media reports Monday.
</P>
<P>
The army hopes to buy enough laser systems to outfit about 1,
000 soldiers and 270 vehicles for the purpose, with a specialized
training center of 180 square kilometers being planned at Canadian
Forces Base Wainwright in Alberta.
</P>
<P>
A computer system would show soldiers what they did wrong and
why they ended up getting "killed" in simulation wars, in which
they were allowed to zap each other or "enemy" vehicles with
lasers attached to their rifles.
</P>
<P>
The so-called weapons effects simulation system will give the
Canadian army the ability for the first time to measure training
effectiveness, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
If approved by the Canadian Treasury Board, the first combat
team of about 250 soldiers and 60 vehicles could be in the field
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British armies operate similar laser training
systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
