<HEADLINE> Former Rwandan Militia Leader Jailed for Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A former Rwandan militia
leader was given a life sentence Monday by the International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) in Tanzania's northern town of
Arusha.
</P>
<P>
An ICTR press release said that Georges Rutaganda, the second
vice- president of Rwanda's notorious Interahamwe militia, was
sentenced to imprisonment for life following his conviction on one
count of genocide and of two counts of crimes against humanity by
the U.N. tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Judges in Trial Chamber One unanimously found that Rutaganda
incurred individual criminal responsibility in particular for
having ordered, incited and carried out murders and for causing
serious bodily or mental harm to members of the Tutsi ethnic group
during the genocide in Rwanda in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Rutaganda had held a high position in the Interahamwe at the
time the crimes were committed.
</P>
<P>
He had knowingly and consciously participated in those crimes
and had shown no remorse for what he had inflicted upon the
victims.
</P>
<P>
Rutaganda, now aged 41, was a member of an influential family
and a prosperous businessman.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested in Zambia in October 1995 and transferred to
the U.N. Detention Facilities in Arusha on May 26, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Defense counsel for Rutaganda, Tiphaine Dickson of the Montreal
Bar announced that she would appeal against the verdict and the
sentence.
</P>
<P>
This judgment is the fifth by the ICTR and brings the number of
 convicted persons to six. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
