<HEADLINE> Roundup: Russians Press Advance on Grozny, Surround Urus-Martan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian units Monday narrowed
the noose around Grozny, capital of the rebelling Chechen republic,
and completely surrounded another key town of Urus-Martan, 20
kilometers southwest of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
During the day the Russian troops in Chechnya fought against
militants mainly in the area of the district capital of Urus-
Martan, said the Russian Defense Ministry press service.
</P>
<P>
Fierce artillery and air strikes were conducted on
concentrations of militants in Grozny, Urus-Martan and other
places around the capital, while federal interior troops completed
their mopping-up operations in Tsentoroi and Alleroi.
</P>
<P>
The press service said that the troops surrounding Grozny still
have a safety corridor left for civilians to escape. However, the
militants are trying everything they can to prevent civilians from
leaving and are using them as living shields.
</P>
<P>
"They are acting just the same in Urus-Martan. They have set up
posts along the roads around the town to stop and force back any
civilians leaving town," the press service said.
</P>
<P>
Self-defense unit led by former mayor of Grozny Bislan
Gantamirov had "ousted militants from the village of Gekhi and
several other communities in the Urus-Martan district," it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian troops are preparing for liberating Grozny.
</P>
<P>
Federal units in Chechnya plan to start the final phase of
liberating Grozny from criminal gangs in coming days, said an
official in the Russian North Caucasus command, cited by the
Interfax news agency Monday.
</P>
<P>
The method used in taking over the towns of Gudermes and Argun
will not be used for this time, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to destroy the large gangs positioned in Grozny
rather than just seize the city," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Chechen field commander Khatab is believed to head the 3,000 to
5,000 militants staying in the city.
</P>
<P>
Chechen leader Aslan Maskhadov still remains in Grozny but is
likely to retreat toward the unliberated south mountain areas.
</P>
<P>
Russians gave the militants December 11 as the deadline for
leaving Grozny and surrendering to federal units.
</P>
<P>
"Your are surrounded. All roads from Grozny have been closed.
Resistance would make no sense. Those staying in the city will be
regarded as terrorists and gangsters and be destroyed by artillery
and the air force," said Russian federal command leaflets dropping
over the city.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no more talks," the command warned.
</P>
<P>
"No frontal attack on Grozny is planned, but first the town of
Urus-Martan has to be seized," said Colonel General Valery Manilov,
deputy chief of the General Staff of the Russian armed force,
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This (the liberation of Urus-Martan) will bring to an end the
first phase of the third stage of the anti-terrorist operation in
Chechnya," Manilov said. At this phase militants will be ousted
from the populated areas of Chechnya into the mountains, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
"At the second phase of the third stage gangsters and
terrorists will be destroyed in the foothills and mountains, where
they have set up bases, camps and stores of ammunition and
foodstuffs," Manilov stated.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Chechnya is developing as our units dictated,
" he noted.
</P>
<P>
While suffering grave losses under the air raids by the federal
force, Chechen bandit formations are preparing for a long partisan
war and sabotage, the Interfax quoted the Russian military
headquarters in the North Caucasus as saying.
</P>
<P>
Chechen warlords Shamil Basayev and Khattab are planning to
retreat into Georgia and to deploy up to 1,000 fighters along its
border with Chechnya if federal troops capture Grozny, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Tu-22M3 "Backfire" medium-range bombers might start carrying
out missions in Chechnya. This aircraft is capable of carrying
powerful high-tech bombs, said the Russian headquarters.
</P>
<P>
An Mi-28 sample helicopter was transported to Mozdok. The Mi-28
carries the latest navigation and focusing equipment. It will help
with the targeting of Mi-24 helicopters at night time and in
unfavorable weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
Russians also plan to use K-50 Black Shark helicopters in mid-
December, which are parked in the Mozdok airbase. They are said to
be effective in the mountains and capable of hitting various
targets.
</P>
<P>
Now over 5,000 militants are concentrated in the Grozny
fortified district. Militants set up strong resistance facilities
in the towns of Urus-Martan, Shali and Vedeno. Separate militant
groups are active in the district of Kurchaloyevsky, said the
Russian front-line military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
