<HEADLINE> African Countries Get New UNDP Aid to Combat Desertification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A new initiative
launched by the U.N. Development Program (UNDP) will help 31
African countries fight desertification and promote local land
management and poverty alleviation initiatives, UNDP officials
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the program, which will focus on capacity-
building in the African countries, was announced by Eimi Watanabe,
director of the UNDP's Bureau for Development Policy, during the
Third Conference of the Parties to the U.N. Convention to Combat
Desertification, which was held in Recife, Brazil, on November 15-
26, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Watanabe said that the initiative is being launched following
urgent requests from African countries for assistance in fighting
desertification.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP Office to Combat Desertification and Drought (UNSO),
is providing 500,000 U.S. dollars in seed funding. Donor
contributions are presently being sought. The program will operate
out of two UNSO centers in East and West Africa.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1965, the UNDP is the world's largest
multilateral source of grants for sustainable human development.
It coordinates most of the technical assistance provided by the
United Nations system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
