<HEADLINE> New Borns Mixed Three Times in Two Months: Canadian Parents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian hospital in Winnipeg
has been accused of mixing new born babies "for the third time in
two months," said a press report Monday from the central Canadian
city.
</P>
<P>
The latest incident happened last Monday when a mother was
given the wrong infant to breastfeed.
</P>
<P>
"Ours was a tiny baby with dark skin and black hair but they
brought her a white, chubby, blond-haired baby to feed,"
complained an agitated father Ryan Punton.
</P>
<P>
Punton's son was taken by a nurse for tests Monday morning. The
parents then were returned with a different baby for feeding,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Punton said the nurse later apologized.
</P>
<P>
The incident came one day after another couple accused the
hospital of the same problem.
</P>
<P>
In September, a woman in the same maternity ward breastfed a
baby for an hour before discovering the boy wasn't her son, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The hospital is asking for a full report of the incidents,
saying, "Certainly it's troubling. It's below the standard of care
we want to provide."
</P>
<P>
The hospital also attributed the problem more or less to a
shortage of nurses, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
