<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Coca-Cola Chairman Announces Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- M. Douglas Ivester, chairman
of Coca-Cola Co., will retire in April after only two years in the
job, the Atlanta-based company announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected move comes as the world's biggest soft drink
maker struggles to recover from a period in which its stock price
sagged, a group of current and former black employees sued
alleging discrimination, and a product-contamination scare cut
into sales across Europe.
</P>
<P>
"After extensive reflection and thought, I have concluded that
it is time for me to move on to the next stage of my life and,
therefore to put into place an orderly transition for this great
company," Ivester was quoted by the Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
At a special meeting Sunday, Coke's board elected 56-year-old
Douglas N. Daft as president and chief operating officer,
effective immediately. The board also said it plans to elect Daft
as Ivester's successor after its April shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ivester, 52, had been Coke's chairman and chief executive
officer since October 1997, when he was chosen to succeed Roberto
C. Goizueta, who had died of cancer.
</P>
<P>
Daft oversees Coke's Middle and Far East Group. Last month, he
was given responsibility for Africa and the company's new
Schweppes Beverages Division.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, while generally optimistic about the company's long-
term prospects, have been disappointed repeatedly by a string of
poor earnings reports that have befallen Coke. Those began in 1997,
when its profits dropped sharply because of economic troubles in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
In June, more than 250 people in Belgium and France reported
becoming sick after drinking Coke products. That led to a brief
sales ban, further hurting profits. Ivester traveled to Europe to
try to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
Coke is also facing a lawsuit brought in April by four current
and former employees, alleging that Coca-Cola pays black employees
less, offers them fewer promotions and gives them lower
performance evaluation scores than whites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
