<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Fight Against Female Genital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) has urged African countries to work together in addressing
the continental problem of female genital mutilation, which has
long existed on the continent.
</P>
<P>
A lot of girls on the continent are constantly at risk of
undergoing this deeply rooted traditional and cultural practice,
WHO representative to Zambia, Edward Maganu, said at a workshop on
female genital mutilation in Lusaka Monday.
</P>
<P>
Female genital mutilation is known to be prevalent in 27
African countries, and is predominant in the eastern and western
parts of the continent.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there are over 120 million girls and women
who have undergone some form of genital mutilation.
</P>
<P>
Maganu noted that while it is important to initiate girls into
womanhood, female genital mutilation has adverse effects on their
health and therefore is not the right way to initiate the girls.
</P>
<P>
He said that elimination of the practice would enhance women's
health, child survival and reduce the risk of contracting sexually
transmitted disease and HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zambian Deputy Minister of Health, Ernest Mwansa,
has cautioned African countries to approach the issue of female
genital mutilation with care.
</P>
<P>
Although harmful in some societies, female genital mutilation
is a way of life, an identity of the people which would not be
done away with overnight, the deputy minister pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He called for extensive research in female genital mutilation
if long- lasting and effective country measures are to be
developed and employed in the fight against the practice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
