<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Host Conference on Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 6 (Xinhua) -- France will host a conference on
Africa from Tuesday in Paris, which will draw foreign ministers
from all African countries except Somalia, said French Foreign
Ministry officials Monday.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has been deprived of a national government since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The conference will be a follow-up of the 20th French-African
summit held here one year ago, during which French President
Jacques Chirac, U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan and African
leaders called on all countries and forces involved in the war in
the Democratic Republic of Congo to stop fighting.
</P>
<P>
But one year after the appeal was made, actions of hostility
are still going on there despite a peace agreement signed in July
in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Algeria, the current president of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU), will send its foreign minister, Ahmed Attaf, to the
conference for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Libya and Sudan, the two African countries which were not
invited to the summit last year, will send their foreign minister
or representative this time.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine and Minister of
Cooperation Charles Josselin will discuss with their African
counterparts the situation in Africa over the past one year.
</P>
<P>
The conference will also decide the hosting country for the
next French-African summit, which is held every two years.
</P>
<P>
Mali and Cameroon have applied for hosting the next summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
