<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relaxation of Regulations Important to Global </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Relaxation of trade regulations
is of great importance to global trade, a senior technical officer
of the World Customs Organization (WCO) said in Harare Monday.
</P>
<P>
Opening up economies is expected to facilitate cooperation
among countries, Kameswari Subramanian told an international
senior customs officials seminar on free flow of goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
"As countries strive for competency in terms of international
trade, it has been of significance to implement policies envisaged
on the accumulation of high revenue margins due to free flow of
goods and services among nations," the WCO official said.
</P>
<P>
She said there are efforts to facilitate the removal of
barriers to trade by simplifying and harmonizing customs
procedures throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa said at the seminar
that the changing economic environment has been characterized by
globalization and regional integration, and reduction of both
tariff and non tariff barriers.
</P>
<P>
He said revenue collection has to be done in a way that does
not disadvantage other nations.
</P>
<P>
Senior customs officials from Botswana, Cuba, Egypt, the
Gambia, Lesotho,

Malawi, Namibia, South Africa, Saudi Arabia, the Sudan, Uganda,
Zambia and Zimbabwe are attending the five-day seminar opened here
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
