<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Britain Block 25 Contracts: Iraqi Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and British envoys at the
U.N. Sanctions Committee recently blocked 25 contracts Iraq signed
under the oil-for-food program, said an Iraqi Trade Ministry
spokesman on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Sanctions Committee put on hold 19 Iraqi contracts during
its sessions held on December 1-3, the spokesman said, quoted by
Iraqi News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The contracts were signed in the fifth and sixth phases of the
oil-for-food deal with companies from Italy, Belarus, Turkey,
Spain, India, China and France for the purchases of oil and
electricity spare parts, medicine and medical appliances, printing
materials, teaching labs and engineering equipment.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Iraqi Health Minister Umid Medhat
Mubarak said on Monday that U.S. and British envoys at the
Sanctions Committee recently suspended six contracts his ministry
concluded with foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
He said those contracts were for the purchases of children's
vaccines, insecticide, vaccines for measles and rabies and lab
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. humanitarian oil-for-food program, Iraq is
allowed to sell 5.2 billion U.S. dollars in oil over six months to
buy food, medicine and infrastructure-related materials for its
people.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has repeatedly accused U.S. and Britain of manipulating
the Sanctions Committee to deliberately hamper the endorsement of
its contracts signed with foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Iraq argues that the oil-for-food deal has failed to alleviate
the sufferings of the Iraqi people, and demands a lifting of the
nine-year-old U.N. sanctions imposed following its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
