<HEADLINE> Nujoma Wins Namibian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam
Nujoma and his Southwest African People's Organization (SWAPO)
have won the presidential and parliamentary elections with more
than 75 percent of votes counted.
</P>
<P>
By early Monday afternoon, with counts outstanding from only two
of Namibia's 103 constituencies, Nujoma had taken 77 percent of
the vote in the presidential election and his SWAPO taken 76
percent in the parliamentary elections, South African Press
Association quoted Namibian Independent Electoral Commission as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma, 70, who has led Namibia since independence in 1990, was
due to make an acceptance speech at 7:00 p.m. local time (1700
GMT) on Monday after the official announcement of the final
results from last week's vote, said Peter Mietzner, spokesman of
the Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
The results showed that the 10-month old Congress of Democrats
(COD), which took ten percent of the votes, had managed to depose
the Democratic Turnhalle Alliance (DTA), which took nine percent,
as the official opposition.
</P>
<P>
Mietzner said the COD and the DTA combined were likely to get 15
seats in the 72-seat national assembly -- the same number the DTA
held by itself before the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
