<HEADLINE> No More Final-Status Talks Until Settlements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians will not
proceed with further final-status talks with Israel until Israeli
government stops expanding Jewish settlements in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, said Palestinian chief negotiator Yasser Abed Rabbo
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the 8th session of final-status talks with his
Israeli counterpart Oded Eran in the West Bank city of Ramallah,
Rabbo said the meeting failed to address the Palestinian refugee
issue as scheduled because of the latest development of Jewish
settlement activities, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the tenders issued Sunday by Israeli Housing
Ministry for constructing 500 new units in settlements in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, adding that the final-status talks and
settlements expanding are totally incompatible things.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel's Peace Now organization had
said that since Prime Minister Ehud Barak came to power five
months ago, his government has published building tenders for
3,196 homes in settlements, which had surpassed the former
government's annual average number.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, U.S. Middle East Special Coordinator Dennis
Ross failed to break the deadlock in the interim and
permanent-status talks when he met with Israeli and Palestinian
negotiation teams.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived here Sunday to prepare for the scheduled visit of
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to Israel on Tuesday
night. He also held talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
and Barak earlier.
</P>
<P>
Israelis and the Palestinians hope that Albright could resolve
the impasse between them, although the two initial objectives of
her visit are to revive the Israeli-Syrian peace moves and to
advance Israeli-Palestinian talks on the final-status
issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
