<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Signs Agreement to Fight Against Sleeping Disease in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (
WHO) and a pharmaceutical company signed here Monday a license
agreement to expand production of a life-saving drug called
eflornithine to treat human African trypanosomiasis.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 55 million people in 36 African countries
south of Sahara are exposed to the risk of contracting human
African trypanosomiasis, also known as sleeping disease. According
to health authorities in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, the
number of deaths due to human trypanosomiasis at least equals to
the number of deaths due to AIDS in two provinces of the largest
central African country.
</P>
<P>
WHO and Hoechst Marion Roussel Inc have been collaborating for
20 years in the development of eflornithine to treat human African
trypanosomiasis. The agreement signed Monday will allow other WHO
partners to produce and distribute the drug.
</P>
<P>
Technology transfer from Hoechst Marion Roussel will take place
once WHO has found a new partner in the private sector capable of
producing eflornithine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
