<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela to Meet Clinton Over Middle East Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 6 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to bring together
the different strands of his Middle East peace initiative, former
South African President Nelson Mandela is to fly to Seattle
Tuesday to meet with U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The US is a key player in any peace settlement in the region,
Mandela said at a press conference in Cape Town Monday.
</P>
<P>
Once leaders like Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair
had become fully involved, the load on him would lessen and he
would be able to give more attention to peace efforts in a country
like Burundi, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela stressed that any settlement in the Middle East has to
be a joint responsibility and collective action of all parties
involved.
</P>
<P>
All initiatives should now be harmonized "so we speak with one
voice", he said.
</P>
<P>
A number of Middle East peace initiatives over the past 25
years had been unsuccessful because countries had been pushing
their own interests, Mandela noted.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the three key elements of his peace proposals:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel has to make an undertaking to withdraw from all the
territories it had conquered in the 1967 seven-day war;
</P>
<P>
-- Arab states have to realize Israel could not withdraw from
all the territories until they stated they recognized the Jewish
state's right to exist within secure boundaries; and
</P>
<P>
-- An international commission has to be set up comprising the
main Arab states, Israel and the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
