<HEADLINE> Committee Finds About 54,000 Holocaust-Era Unclaimed Accounts in Swiss                  Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- An international committee
investigating Swiss banks have found about 54,000 unclaimed
accounts that may be linked to Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
A total of 53,886 such accounts, about 10 times as much as the
Swiss banks themselves had said they had discovered, were found as
a result of three-year search of 59 Swiss banks for accounts
opened while the Nazis held power in neighboring Germany from 1933
to 1945, according to a report published Monday by the Independent
Committee of Eminent Persons.
</P>
<P>
The probe also included about 30,000 closed accounts. The
committee, established in 1996 by Swiss bankers and Jewish groups
and chaired by former U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Paul A.
Volcker, recommended that the names of the 25,000 dormant accounts
should be made public so that relatives can file claims. Two years
ago, Swiss banks published 5,559 names on missing account holders
who lived outside Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
While auditors found no evidence of systematic destruction of
dormant account information, some banks were criticized for
stonewalling by the committee in its final report.
</P>
<P>
However, the committee praised the Swiss banks' cooperation in
uncovering the truth about the dormant accounts and said attitudes
had clearly changed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Swiss Bankers Association said it considered the
report fair, and said it regretted cases of improper behavior
listed by the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
