<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Companies Lag In Capital Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- British companies are continuing
to invest at levels well below their international competitors,
underpinning Britain's poor productivity record, according to an
official survey released Monday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the 1999 Capex Scoreboard, a survey of capital
spending by 500 British and 300 international companies, Lord
Sainsbury, science minister, warned several sectors needed to wake
up to the challenge posed by big foreign firms.
</P>
<P>
Across all the 33 industrial sectors, British companies last
year spent 75 billion pounds on plant and equipment. That amounted
to 10,000 pounds for each of their employees, compared with 15,200
pounds for international businesses.
</P>
<P>
Six companies alone -- Shell, BP Amoco, BT, Cable &AMP; Wireless,
British Airways and Railtrack -- account for a quarter of the 75
billion pounds last year.
</P>
<P>
The UK spends just 9.2 percent of its total capital expenditure
on physics-based companies, compared with a 23.2 percent share for
international companies. In telecoms, it spends 9.7 percent,
compared with 17 percent internationally.
</P>
<P>
Norman Price, an industrialist in the Department of Trade and
Industry, said: "Capital spending is material wrapped around
knowledge. Without it and other knowledge investment, companies
will struggle to innovate and remain competitive in the global
market." 
</P>
</TEXT>
