<HEADLINE> UN Secretary-General Resumes Cyprus Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus talks began
Monday morning at 11 a.m. when U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
and his Special Adviser Alvaro de Soto met with Glafcos Clerides,
President of Cyprus and the leader of the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said the U.N. chief then met with
Rauf Denktash, the leader of the Turkish Cypriots, at 12:15 p.m,
and over the weekend, de Soto met with each of the parties.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the United Nations expected the talks to
take place on a daily basis, until either the parties feel they
can no longer make progress or until a breakthrough is achieved.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has tentatively scheduled 10 days for the
talks but is prepared for longer talks if necessary, said Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.- brokered "proximity talks " between the two parties
opened at the U.N. Headquarters in New York Friday. "Proximity
talks" mean that the parties are within reach but they will not
meet face to face. The U.N. coordinators shuttle between them.
</P>
