<HEADLINE> EU Ministers Concern Over Chechen Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
foreign ministers expressed "deep concern" over the current
situation in Chechnya when they met here to prepare for this week'
s EU summit in Helsinki, urging the Russian government to refrain
from using excessive force in Chechnya and to respect the
principles of international humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
In a conclusion about today's meeting, the ministers said the
present campaign and "the unacceptable threat to the people of
Grozny can only perpetuate, not break, the cycle of violence in
the Northern Caucasus".
</P>
<P>
They said the EU is deeply worried by the news that civilians
in Grozny have been given an ultimatum to leave by December 11 or
face annihilation. The ministers hold the Russian government
responsible for the humanitarian situation in the region and urge
it to fulfill its commitments under international humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
They said the EU Council of ministers "considers it of the
utmost importance that the international humanitarian aid agencies
are able to assist the victims of the Chechen war".
</P>
<P>
They also urged the Chechen authorities to respect the rules
and principles of humanitarian law, to condemn terrorism and to
aim at the renewal of a political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, all the 15 ministers of the EU member
states also reiterated the EU's position on the territorial
integrity of the Russian Federation and its resolute condemnation
of terrorism in all its forms. 
</P>
