<HEADLINE> Canadian Nurses Warn of Shortage of 100,000 by 2021 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian Nurses Association(
CNA) are warning of a shortfall of 100,000 nurses by 2021, while a
group of doctors said the country needs a yearly 540 to 600
additional doctors, the Ottawa Citizen newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In its recent letter to the country's federal and provincial
health ministers, CNA said the average age of a nurse is now 47
and there are fewer entering the profession than those retiring.
</P>
<P>
Only 5 percent of nurses are under the age of 30, CNA said,
warning" such a lack of registered nursing staff in the health-
care system will pose a serious threat to public safety."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile a task force of Canadian doctors said in their
documents that they believe about 3.5 percent of the now 56,000
Canadian doctors will retire, die, emigrate or leave practice each
year.
</P>
<P>
In the backdrop of a yearly increase of 350,000 in the country'
s population, Canada requires 540 to 600 additional doctors
annually, they said.
</P>
<P>
The documents indicate the current shortage of doctors and
nurses will only grow worse in the next decade as the aging
population requires more health care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
