<HEADLINE> Mozambican Electoral Process "Satisfactory": EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The joint observation mission of
the European Union (EU) said in Maputo Monday that the Mozambican
electoral process has been "peaceful, orderly and satisfactory,"
with between 75 percent and 80 percent of the voters having cast
their ballots.
</P>
<P>
The EU observation mission said in a press release that its 64
observers have visited 34 counties in the 11 provinces in the
southern African country and monitored the voting at 750 polling
stations, nine percent of the 8,324 stations across the country.
</P>
<P>
Among the observers are members of parliament, experts and
scholars, some of whom have been in Mozambique before.
</P>
<P>
The EU observation mission arrived in Mozambique late last
month to monitor the country's second multi-party elections on
December 3-5.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. President Jimmy Carter who is leading 50 observers
in Mozambique, also said here Monday that the Mozambican electoral
process has been "overwhelmingly free and fair".
</P>
<P>
Counting took place at the polling stations on Sunday night.
Provincial results should be announced by December 12, and a week
later the National Elections Commission should announce the final
results. 
</P>
