<HEADLINE> Basic Health Care Guaranteed in Ethiopia: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- There is no scarcity of
basic medicines and medical equipment at present in Ethiopia, an
official with the Ethiopian Drug Administration and Control said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
There are reliable basic medicines for malaria, tuberculosis,
mother and child care, family planning and vaccines, said
Mengestab Wolde-Aregai.
</P>
<P>
Medicines and medical equipment are imported through donation,
credit, as well as importers and wholesale enterprises, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Mengestab noted that there could be artificial
shortage of basic medicines due to lack of coordinated efforts and
delay of supply.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, Ethiopia imported medicines and
medical equipment worth 700 million birr (about 85 million U.S.
dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Besides, medicines and medical equipment worth some 250 million
birr (31 million dollars) were also secured from donors and
distributed to states to implement regular and pressing programs
of the Ministry of Health, he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are five pharmaceutical and medical equipment
factories, 70 wholesale distributors, 2,300 drug stores, as well
as some 4,000 private and government-owned health organizations in
Ethiopia, Mengestab said. 
</P>
