<HEADLINE> Panama Denies US Prepared Security Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 6 (Xinhua)-- The Panamanian government
denied Monday the United States supervised the elaboration of the
Strategic Plan of National Security after taking out of American
forces from the canal.
</P>
<P>
Panama's Head of the Public Security Council and National
Defense Pablo Quinetero Luna said, "Panamanian authorities no
longer are kinder children needing to have their teacher at one
side."
</P>
<P>
Legislator Miguel Bush said last Friday that Washington
prepared the document regarding Panama's national security made
known recently by Panama's Interior and Justice Minister Winston
Spadafora.
</P>
<P>
United States only guided and backed Panama's government
indicating to it where more care should be taken and indicating
sensitive points in the area of the interoceanioc Canal, said the
Interior Minister.
</P>
<P>
According to Quintero Luna, it's time to leave "the Pentagon
umbrella", referring to the strong tutorship that for nearly one
century successive American governments held upon this Central
American country.
</P>
<P>
The Strategic Plan of National Security, presented by
Panamanian government, views as risk factors the exit of U.S.
forces from Panama, drug traffic, corruption and illegal
immigration.
</P>
<P>
According to this plan, with the exit of American soldiers, a
dissuading factor favorable for the Canal's safety will stop. The
Canal will be handed back by United States to Panama on December
31.
</P>
<P>
In order to stop risk factors, the Strategic Plan anticipated
establishing a network of international accords for structuring a
national security system based on bilateral agreements, set to
guarantee a sure and neutral transit of the Canal.
</P>
<P>
Although an accord between United States and Panama isn't
mentioned, Panamanian political analysts consider that with this
Strategic Plan doors are opened for a novel agreement guaranteeing
U.S. military influence after year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
