<HEADLINE> 4 Wounded in U.S. School Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Four students were wounded
as their 13-year-old classmate opened fire with a semiautomatic
handgun outside a middle school in Fort Gibson of Oklahoma State,
the United States, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The wounded were taken to hospitals in Tulsa and Muskogee, and
none of the injuries appeared life-threatening, the reports quoted
local police as saying.
</P>
<P>
Students were gathered outside before the start of classes at 8
a.m. local time when the shooting began. It was not known how many
shots were fired.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, President Bill Clinton told reporters that
investigators were on the scene.
</P>
<P>
"Our prayers are with each of the children and their families,"
Clinton said. "Right now there are no fatalities, only people who
are wounded, and we hope it will stay that way."
</P>
<P>
Fort Gibson is a town of some 3,500 people about 80 kilometers
southeast of Tulsa. About 450 students attend the middle school.
</P>
