<HEADLINE> Three People Killed in Assault on Armored Cash-carrying Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to Italian news agency Ansa, the local police on the
scene said the lead armored car of two traveling in convoy was
violently rammed by a truck on a provincial highway near Lecce, on
the heel of the Italian peninsula.
</P>
<P>
One of the armed guards killed may have died in the collision,
they said.
</P>
<P>
At that point, the driver of the second armored car attempted
to make a U-turn but was blocked by a Nissan Patrol 4-wheel drive
vehicle and gunmen who stepped out firing.
</P>
<P>
The assailants then used explosives to open up the armored car
in blasts which killed two of the occupants instantly.
</P>
<P>
Three of the six armed guards, none of whom had time to draw
their weapons, were injured by shots fired by the assailants
during the robbery.
</P>
<P>
Police said the robbers than made their getaway aboard the
Nissan Patrol and another automobile with the contents of both
armored cars, estimated at about three billion lire (about 1.58
million U.S. dollars
</P>
<P>
They also recalled a similar assault in the vicinity on
November 2 on a lone armored car operated by the same company, the
Velialpol Security Agency, which netted the robbers more than one
billion lire(about 526,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In both cases, the cash was intended for distribution to post
offices for the payment of pension benefits.
</P>
<P>
Also Monday, on the other side of the Gulf of Taranto, gunmen
firing Kalashnikovs and pistols overwhelmed the driver of an
armored car and an armed guard on a state highway near southern
city of Cosenza, in central Calabria region, and made off with 600
million lire (about 316,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Both occupants of the armored car were hospitalized in Cosenza
with injuries which were reportedly not serious. 
</P>
</TEXT>
