<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Plans to Join WTO in Two Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan plans to join the
World Trade Organization (WTO) in the nearest two years, said
Kazakh Economy Minister Zhaksybek Kulekeyev Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, Kulekeyev told a press
conference in the Kazakh capital of Astana that Kazakhstan
announced its application for the WTO membership in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is difficult to name any concrete date, he said, adding that
"this will depend not only on Kazakhstan, but also on WTO member
states with which Kazakhstan will have to hold bilateral talks and
sign appropriate agreements."
</P>
<P>
The WTO demands low customs tariffs on goods and services from
its members. Kazakhstan has already submitted its proposals on
shaping customs tariffs to the WTO, said Kulekeyev.
</P>
<P>
Now the country has a real chance of becoming a WTO member
within the next two years, he said.
</P>
<P>
After joining the WTO, Kazakhstan will gain real access to the
world's markets by exporting textiles, fabrics, food stuffs and
other items to the West, although today the nation mostly exports
raw and other materials, Kulekeyev said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Kazakhstan's future WTO membership would not
affect the trading ties among the CIS (the Commonwealth of
Independent States) Customs Union countries, which includes
Kazakhstan, Russia, Belarus, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
