<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat's Advisor Terms Settlement Expansion Cause </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official has
termed the continued settlement activities cause of the crisis
that has deadlocked the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Abu Rudeineh, media advisor to Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat made the remarks Tuesday in
response to Israeli chief negotiator Oded Eran's claim that the
PNA was trying to create a crisis on the eve of U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright's visit to Israel on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Abu Rudeineh said Albright will convey the message to Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak that Israel's settlement policy will
hinder the final-status talks and settlements expansion is illegal
according to international resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the international community supports the
Palestinian demands for a cessation of settlement activities, and
warned that continued settlement activities will lead to the
collapse of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side boycotted the eighth session of the
final-status negotiations Monday, saying no more talks if Israel
does not stop settlements building.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Ministry of Housing issued tenders for building 500 new
housing units in two settlements in the West Bank, which angered
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a meeting between Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb
Erekat and Eran scheduled for Tuesday in Jerusalem for the
transition-phase negotiations has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
During her stay in Israel, Albright will hold talks with Barak,
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy on the peace process,
particularly the final-status and interim phase negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Albright will also meet Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in a
bid to defuse the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said Monday that
Albright would tell Israeli officials that settlement activities
stood in the way to a final peace agreement expected next
September.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli side has softened its stance on the settlement
issue, with on Monday evening reaffirming that no new tenders were
issued for settlements building, saying that such buildings would
harm the prestige of Israel worldwide and would damage
negotiations with the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
