<HEADLINE> Thai Refinery Ordered to Shut Down for Three Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Industry Ministry of
Thailand Tuesday ordered Thai Oil Co. to shut down its refinery,
which was badly damaged in the fire over the weekend, for three
months.
</P>
<P>
A ministry spokesman told reporters that the three-month
closure period will start from Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that if the refinery can be repaired earlier,
the ministry will consider shortening the closure period.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's decision came after an inspection to the
refinery, which is located in an industrial zone some 90
kilometers southeast of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
An explosion occurred in the refinery at late Thursday night
and the fire afterwards raged on for 35 hours before being put out
on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
The fire killed seven people and destroyed some 40 million
liters of gasoline in four storage tanks, causing the company 500
to 800 million baht (12.9 to 20.7 million U.S. dollars) in losses.
</P>
<P>
In wake of the disaster, the Industry Ministry decided to
inspect over 100 plants which carry risks of explosion and are
located in community areas.
</P>
<P>
The emphasis of the inspection will be placed on industrial
plants with petrochemical, oil and explosive materials.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Petroleum Authority of Thailand played down
speculations that suspension of the operation of Thai Oil's plant,
one of the country's largest oil refineries, will affect local
gasoline supplies.
</P>
<P>
Five other refineries, which had been running below their
capacities, are able to substitute the supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
