<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Universities Encouraged to Implement AIDS-Free Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Universities in Malaysia
are encouraged to set up clubs with the government financial and
other assistance to promote AIDS-free life style among
undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry is actively encouraging tertiary
institutions to set up such clubs to help in the government's anti-
aids programs and the ministry will provide these clubs with
advisory service, expertise and also financial aid, Health
Services Department Deputy Director-General Abdul Aziz Mahmood
said Tuesday in Kuala Terengganu, some 450 kilometers northeast
from here, according to Bernama News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The government encourages tertiary institutions to take part in
the anti-aids programs as adults in the 20-39 age group formed the
largest segment of the country's HIV/AIDS sufferers, he said,
adding that of the 32,297 HIV/AIDS cases detected in Malaysia from
1986 to September last year, 28,816 involved those in the age
group.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's other efforts in enhancing public awareness
about the Aids scourge include screening expectant mothers for HIV,
the virus that causes Aids since 1986, the official told reporters
after launching the national-level World Aids Day celebration
there.
</P>
<P>
Of the 250,000 expectant mothers screened since then, only 100
were HIV-infected and given treatment, following which only five
of the babies delivered inherited the disease, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the World Health Organization (WHO) had
forecast significant increase in the number of HIV/Aids sufferers
in the first three years of the new century especially among
teenagers world-wide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Has Easy World Cup Draw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Asian soccer powerhouse Saudi
Arabia is expected to have a comfortable start after Tuesday's
draw for the qualifying campaign of the 2002 World Cup here.
</P>
<P>
The Saudis, who reached the second round of USA '94 and also
qualified for France '98, has been paired with Vietnam, Bangladesh
and Mongolia, all which are hard to cause problems to Saudi Arabia,
currently ranked by FIFA the top team in Asia.
</P>
<P>
China also have a kinder group although they need to clear the
hurdle set by Indonesia, the strongest of the second-ranked Asian
teams. The other members of Group nine are Maldives and Cambodia,
which was recently brushed out of the Asian Cup by Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Asian Games champions Iran face a tougher task in group two,
which includes former Soviet republic Tajikstan, as well as
minnows Myanmar and Guam.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also has a hard job as they are obliged to battle another
former Soviet republic, Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's prospects of reaching the second qualifying round
were given a boost when they were drawn in group five with Lebanon,
Sri Lanka and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The 10 group winners qualify for final round which will be
divided into two groups of five teams. The two winners of the
final round groups qualify for the finals in Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The two runners-up will play off for the right to meet a
European group runner-up in a further play-off. The winner of this
play-off qualifies for the finals.
</P>
<P>
In Africa the five African representatives at the 1998 finals
in France - Cameroon, Morocco, Nigeria, South Africa, Tunisia -
should have little trouble reaching the mini-league second phase.
</P>
<P>
The draws are Cameroon vs Somalia, Nigeria vs Eritrea, Morocco
vs Gambia, South Africa vs Lesotho and Tunisia vs Mauritania with
the minnows having home advantage first.
</P>
<P>
Among the leading African football nations Ghana were handed
the most difficult tasks as they drew with Tanzania, who they
sweated to overcome at the same stage of the 1998 qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania drew 0-0 at home and lost 2-1 away in their previous
clash and a recent Olympic Games qualifier between the countries
also produced two tight matches before Ghana advanced.
</P>
<P>
The 25 first-round winners go into a fresh draw, where they
will be divided into five groups with the winners qualifying for
the World Cup tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
