<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Loan to China to Fight Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
approved Tuesday a loan totaling 102 million U.S. dollars to China
to back the country to fight pollution in industrial cities.
</P>
<P>
According to an ADB press release here, the money will be used
for the environment information project in three cities in Shanxi
province. The total cost of the project is 183 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, a new coke-oven gas manufacturing plant
will be built in Taiyuan, capital of Shanxi province, to supply
gas and coke to replace coal.
</P>
<P>
Also the project is designed to construct two boilers and a
district heating transmission network in Datong and a system to
recover methane gas from an existing coal mine in Yangquan.
</P>
<P>
The project will reduce coal in use by nearly 850,000 tons
annually, the Manila-based ADB said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that burning coal is the number one cause of air
pollution in China.
</P>
<P>
China is starting to make massive investment to enhance
environment protection, the ADB said, adding that it is providing
loans and policy advice to support the fight against pollution in
some of China's worst affected areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
