<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Helps Sri Lanka Protect Vanishing Shore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
approved Tuesday a loan totalling 40 million U.S. dollars to Sri
Lanka to help shore up its vanishing coastline.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here, the ADB said the money will be
used for the Coastal Resource Management Project which will
construct shoreline protection works in the most affected
coastline in six districts along the western coast.
</P>
<P>
The coast is home to a third of the population and the highly
productive ecosystem is an important base for the country's growth,
the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the eroding coastline threatens economic activity
on the western and south western coasts.
</P>
<P>
The project will benefit the small-scale fishers, prawn farmers
in the fishing industry and allied field, the ADB noted.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be repayable over 32 years, including a grace
period of 8 years, and the interest charge will be one percent
annum during the grace period and 1.5 percent per annum thereafter,
it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
