<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Insists on Surveillance of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa, also Chairman of the ruling Revolutionary Party of
Tanzania (CCM), insists that serious issues, such as the
constitutional reform, must get the approval of the party, local
media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a gathering of thousands of CCM members and
supporters here on Monday to commend the government for its
handling of the illness, death and burial of former president
Julius Nyerere, Mkapa said recommendations of the Presidential
Committee on proposed constitutional reform must be approved by
CCM before they are sent to the parliament for any changes.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper quoted him as saying the report on
constitutional reform, the White Paper Report, was made public
last Saturday and had been discussed by the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
"However, before it is sent to Parliament, the report and the
views of the Cabinet must pass the test of the CCM Central
Committee and the National Executive Committee (NEC) to ensure
that it is in agreement with party policies," he said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that in handling the report, the government would
respect the public views as well as the party policies.
</P>
<P>
However, the president said, nobody could push the government
on how to treat the recommendations contained in the report, even
the opposition could do nothing.
</P>
<P>
CCM stands for a two-government structure (the Union government
and the Zanzibar government) in the country. It is reported that
the majority of the interviewees favored the status quo, but the
constitutional reform committee recommended a three-government
union (the Union government, the mainland government and the
Zanzibar government) on grounds that the interviewees' opinions
were conditional and did not meet current demands.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa formed the constitutional reform committee last year to
seek public opinions on constitutional reforms and the committee
handed him a report in June this year, which was made public by
the State House last Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
