<HEADLINE> U.S. Congressmen Pledge Debt Relief for Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States congressmen
have pledged debt relief for Nigeria and the recovery of stolen
money in American banks to facilitate the growth of democracy in
the country.
</P>
<P>
When a group of U.S. congressmen visited Nigeria's National
Assembly in Abuja on Monday, some of them said that they believed
in debt relief rather than debt rescheduling, Daily Times
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some members of the visiting American congress delegation led
by House Minority Leader Richard Gephart have initiated a lobby
group to seek for the remittance of billions of Dollars illegally
stashed away in American banks by unscrupulous Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
Maxine Waters, member of the delegation which arrived here last
Sunday, said that American congress was aware of the heavy debt
Nigeria owed international communities and would rather see some
of such cancelled than rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
On recovery of Nigeria's stole wealth abroad, she said that
American congress was willing to help Nigeria recover any of her
stolen money in American banks.
</P>
<P>
During a recent state visit to Washington, President Olusegun
Obasanjo appealed to President Bill Clinton to write off the debt
owed the United States as the West african country is being
weighed down by huge foreign debts totalling about 30 billion
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The American lawmakers who are on a ten-day visit to three
African countries are scheduled to meet President Obasanjo,
Foreign Minister Sule Lamido and other officials before leaving
for Zimbabwe and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Highlights of the trip will include the dedication of a
U.S.-funded HIV/ AIDS counselling and testing center in Hwange,
Zimbabwe, and the signing of an Overseas Private Investment
Corporation agreement in Abuja, capital of Nigeria, according to
an official of the American embassy to Nigeria.  
</P>
</TEXT>
