<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Ruling Party Denies Claims by Former </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's ruling Frelimo
(Frente de Libertacao de Mocambique) Monday denied claims made by
Renamo (Resistencia Nacional de Mocambique), the former rebel
movement, on provoking violence during the elections.
</P>
<P>
Renamo earlier accused Frelimo of harassing its members and
preventing them from carrying out election campaign activities in
the districts of Changara, Cahora Bassa and Magoe, all in the
western province of Tete, according to Mozambican News Agency
report.
</P>
<P>
Mariano Matsinha, head of the Frelimo election office, told a
Maputo press conference that there had indeed been violence in
these three districts, but he blamed Renamo for having started it.
</P>
<P>
The worst incident was in Changara, where a gang of about 40
Renamo supporters from outside the area "invaded" the district
capital Luenha, Matsinha said.
</P>
<P>
"They beat up people, including an old man. The local people
were revolted at this and turned on them," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Matsinha, the Renamo supporters then fled and took
refuge in the police station. The police then evacuated them to
Tete city.
</P>
<P>
He said the incident had nothing to do with Sergio Vieira,
rapporteur of the current Frelimo parliamentary group, who was
coordinating much of the Frelimo campaign in Tete. Renamo claimed
that Vieira had "orchestrated" the Changara events.
</P>
<P>
Matsinha said he regretted that Renamo has not escaped from its
normal behaviour of denigrating all the processes and institutions
that are fighting for the real democratization of the country, and
for the normalization of the life of Mozambican citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
