<HEADLINE> Asian Financial Crisis Changes Banking Business Models </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Asian financial crisis
during 1997-1998 has changed the environment quite significantly
for the banking and financial sector in the region, a financer
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis brought forward and compressed the
timeframe that banks in every countries have to change their
business models or change the way they are doing things, Nazif
Mohammed, general manager for Oracle Corporation South Asia region
financial services industry, said at a press conference here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that in a period beyond five to 10 years from now, only
the big banks will survive while the smaller ones would have to
merge with larger players to be able to attract customers and make
the investment required.
</P>
<P>
He saw the need for the banks to understand their customers,
what products and services the customers buy from the banks and
the profit the customers contribute to the bank.
</P>
<P>
"Before the crisis, banks in Malaysia were looking at year 2000-
2010 for the deregulations but now with the crisis, the banks are
internally forced to consolidate," he said.
</P>
<P>
He was of the view that as long as the Malaysian environment is
protected, the banks here are relatively safe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
