<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Ends Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 7 (Xinhua) -- United States Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright left Riyadh for Syria Tuesday after
wrapping up her two-day visit to Saudi Arabia, during which she
discussed with Saudi leaders the Iraq issue and the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who is on a Middle East tour which also includes
Syria, Egypt, Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas, held
talks with Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz after arriving in the
Saudi capital of Riyadh late Monday.
</P>
<P>
James Rubin, spokesman for the U.S. State Department, told a
news conference in Riyadh Monday night that Albright and Saudi
leaders reviewed the efforts at the U.N. Security Council aimed at
forging a mechanism on dealing with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Rubin, who is accompanying Albright, said the two sides agreed
on the importance of the Security Council's endorsement of a
decision to set up an appropriate mechanism on suspension of
international sanctions on Iraq if it agrees to the return of the
weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has been debating on a draft
resolution which calls for the return of arms inspectors to Iraq
in exchange for a suspension of sanctions which have been in place
since Baghdad's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
A body of mostly Western nations at the United Nations is set
to vote this week in the Security Council on the draft resolution.
</P>
<P>
Washington strongly advocates a resumption of the U.N. arms
inspection mission in Iraq, which was aborted after the
U.S.-British air-strikes against Iraqi targets last December.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq is demanding the sanctions lifted unconditionally,
insisting that its banned weapons of mass destruction have already
been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
According to Rubin, the U.S. top diplomat also briefed her
Saudi hosts on Washington's efforts to push forward the Middle
East peace process, mainly on the Israeli-Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
A new round of talks between Israel and the Palestinians on an
overdue Israeli withdrawal from 5 percent of the West Bank
stumbled into deadlock after the government of Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak issued more tenders Sunday for construction of
Jewish settlements in the occupied Arab land.
</P>
<P>
But diplomatic sources in Riyadh said Albright would like to
see the two sides work out their difference over the planned
Israeli pullback on the table on their own, according to the
Kuwait News Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
