<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sub-Saharan Countries Urged To Grow Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Crops Research
 Institute Tuesday called on the sub-Saharan countries to grow
drought resistant crops in order to alleviate perennial food
shortages in the region.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Leslie Swindale, Interim Director of the
International Crops Research Institute for the Semi-Arid Tropics,
at a three-day workshop looking into the revival of agricultural
village level studies in Africa and Asia held in Matopos of west
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Most countries in Africa do not encourage their farmers to grow
drought resistant crops such as sorghum and millet but put more
emphasis on maize which suited areas with good rains, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is too much government pressure on farmers to grow maize
instead of sorghum and millet because maize is considered to be
more profitable. However, this has resulted in food shortages as
maize tends not to do well when there is little rainfall," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said there is a general shortage of sorghum and millet seeds
which he blamed on government policies.
</P>
<P>
The director told the workshop that his research institute has
done a lot of research and come up with different crop varieties
that are drought resistant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
