<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Employment Continue to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Tuesday that employment in the Philippines is expected to rise
between 3.31 percent to 3.57 percent annually from 1999 and reach
33.94 million to 34.44 million by 2004.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, the Department of Labor and
Employment(DOLE) said that the government's efforts to make skills
and training even more effective and relevant to boot the
employability and competitiveness of marginalized, vulnerable and
disadvantaged workers, will propel the nation's employment growth
beyond 2000.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment rate, on the other hand, is projected at 7.8
percent by 2004, it said.
</P>
<P>
The DOLE said that the key employment generators would include
infrastructure building, trade and investment, small and medium
enterprise development, tourism as well as agricultural
development.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Labor Secretary Bienvenido Laguesma said employment
gains were registered in many areas nationwide in 1999, boosting
the nation's efforts to overcome the effects of last year's
debilitating drought and a regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The positive employment trend in the first three quarters of
1999 has enabled the nation to offset and surmount the negative
declines in jobs last year, Laguesma said.
</P>
<P>
Labor and employment statistics showed that the total number of
employed persons rose by 2.4 percent, 5.9 percent and 4.3 percent
in January, April and July 1999.
</P>
<P>
The labor chief said the recent employment gains would pave the
way for greater progress in the year 2000 and beyond. 
</P>
</TEXT>
