<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti PM Heads to U.S. For Medical Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Crown Prince and
Prime Minister Sheikh Saad al-Abdullah al-Sabah left here Tuesday
for the United States to receive further medical check-ups and
treatment, state-run Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Saad, who spent more than two months in Britain this
summer receiving medical check-ups and treatment, cut short his
stay and returned to Kuwait late October to attend the inaugural
session of the second term of the 9th parliament.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Saad, who usually receives medical services in London,
told editors-in-chief of local newspapers on Sunday that "despite
the advice of my doctors who asked me not to return, I insisted on
coming back because my country needed me and my services."
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers and official media actually began on Monday a
respectful but somber send-off for the heir to the throne by
praising his deeds and hoped for his quick recovery and return.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Saad, born in 1930, suffered bleeding in the colon two
years ago, which Kuwaiti officials said did not call for much
concern.
</P>
<P>
Saad, educated in Kuwait and at Britain's Hendon Police
Training School, started his career with Kuwait's police in
1945. He held the defense and interior portfolios from mid 1960s
to late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
He has been Crown Prince and Prime Minister since 1978. His
father, late Emir Sheikh Abdullah al-Salem al-Sabah who was in
office in 1950-1965, oversaw the 1961 independence from Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
