<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 traffic
offenders have been charged in KwaZulu-Natal Province, South
Africa since the national launch of the Arrive Alive Campaign in
November, provincial road traffic inspectorate spokesman Vijen
Murugan said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
No mercy would be shown to those who violate traffic
regulations, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Murugan, the traffic flow to KwaZulu-Natal, one of
South Africa's prime holiday spots, is expected to increase around
December 15 when most businesses would close for the Christmas and
New Year events.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman warned motorists not to be fooled by an apparent
lack of visible patrols in some areas because unmarked cars fitted
with sophisticated equipment would be out in full force.
</P>
<P>
Some vehicles were equipped with video recorders and speed
detectors which could spot traffic offenders, he said, adding
recordings of these offences could be used as evidence in court.
</P>
<P>
He said the so-called booze buses would be deployed to test for
drunk drivers and roadblocks would be conducted frequently.
</P>
