<HEADLINE> Official Removed from Post in Southwest China for Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior official has been
dismissed from all his positions within the Communist Party of
China (CPC) in southwest China's Yunnan Province on corruption
charges, sources from the CPC Central Commission for Discipline
Inspection (CCDI) and the Ministry of Supervision said today.
</P>
<P>
With the approval of the CPC Central Committee, the CCDI also
suggested Yunnan's Provincial People's Congress Standing Committee
remove Sun Xiaohong, president of the Higher People's Court in
Yunnan, from his post as president and as a deputy to the 9th
provincial People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Sun has been convicted of smuggling two Audi limousines into
China, one of which he used for his own purposes, in 1997 and 1998
respectively. Customs estimate indicates an evasion of 637,000
yuan in duty in the two smuggling cases.
</P>
<P>
During the 1992-1997 period, while acting as president of the
Intermediate People's Court of Kunming City, Sun allowed the court
to conceal more than 77 million yuan of income, and in the 1992-
1995 period, he approved the distribution of over 1.5 million yuan
of procedural fees as bonuses.
</P>
<P>
A notice issued by the CCDI called on the younger generation of
officials to learn from Sun's case, and to stay clear-headed so as
to better serve the public.  
</P>
</TEXT>
