<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Implement Greenhouse Gas Reducing Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will implement a
project aimed at reducing greenhouse gases emissions by 10 percent,
the Malaysian Energy Center said in a statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The project, called the Malaysian Industrial Energy Efficiency
Improvement Project, at a cost of about 80 million ringgit (21.052
million U.S. dollars) will be implemented over a four-year period
beginning next month, it said.
</P>
<P>
It is co-funded by the United Nations Development Program, the
Malaysian government and private organizations, according to the
center.
</P>
<P>
One of the project's immediate objectives is to remove barriers
for energy efficiency measures in eight sectors -- food, iron and
steel, rubber, cement, ceramic, glass, paper and wood -- by 2004
within the stipulated budget.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed at enabling Malaysia to have a strong
institutional and technical foundation for efforts to capture
energy efficiency potentials in the industrial sector, and also at
creating a sustainable institutional capacity to provide energy
efficiency technical assistance and a conducive policy, planning
and research framework.
</P>
<P>
The center said that improving energy efficiency in Malaysian
industries would contribute towards competitiveness of the
Malaysian economy, which would lead to increased income for its
citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
