<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Government Agencies Secured Against Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's government ministries and
agencies and the public sector have been secured against the Y2K
bug, the country's Middle East News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Communications and Information Ahmad Nazef told the
People's Assembly (Parliament) on Monday that the computer systems
in the essential state sectors, including oil, communications,
health care, banks, aviation and the Suez Canal have been ready
for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt will experience no chaos in its computer systems when
the calendar rolls over to double zero with the advent of the year
2000," he was quoted by the news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most older computers, computerized equipment and software
programs were programmed to recognize only the last two digits of
a year. These computers may misread the year 2000 as 1900, causing
technical malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
This confusion can affect the computer systems for electricity,
water, payrolls, elevators and gas pumps.
</P>
<P>
Egypt formed a technical committee as part of its 1998
government program toward fending off the chaos that is expected
to occur around the world because of the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
The government worked out a six-phase plan to define the
problem in older computer systems, adjust the systems to confront
any technical faults and chart emergency plans for any
eventualities, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt is lucky as most of its systems were installed in the
1990s and are relatively new and safe," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
