<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Samaranch Steps into Wembley Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) president Juan Antonio Samaranch stepped into the
row over the future of London's Wembley stadium on Tuesday when he
said that an arena holding 65,000 spectators would be big enough
to host the Summer Games, according to a report from Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
Last week the British government, with its eyes on a possible
2012 Olympic bid as well as on its campaign to host the 2006
soccer World Cup, gave Wembley chiefs 14 days to find a better way
of rebuilding the stadium so it could stage track and field as
well as soccer.
</P>
<P>
The demand came after Sports Minister Kate Hoey commissioned a
special architectural report as plans showed it would only be able
to accommodate around 65,000 for athletics events.
</P>
<P>
But in an interview with Reuters, the IOC president said: "I
think 65,000 is enough. I think Barcelona (which hosted the 1992
Summer Olympic Games) was less than 60,000. Why not? For me, it is
enough.
</P>
<P>
"In the Olympic Games and the World Cup, the number of
spectators, 60,000 to 65,000 is enough. The importance is the
billions of people watching on television. We have no rules there
must be 65,000, 80,000 or 90,000."
</P>
<P>
The IOC president added that the Stade de France arena, the
venue of last year's World Cup final which can be switched easily
into a venue for athletics, was the perfect solution.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at IOC headquarters, Samaranch said: "I will never
advise building two stadiums. One is enough. For me, the best
solution is the Paris solution."
</P>
<P>
The new $773 million Wembley stadium is due to open in 2003 --
just two years before the venue for the 2012 Summer Olympic Games
is decided by the IOC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
