<HEADLINE> Malaysia Denies Report on Attempt to Foster Ties with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Tuesday denied a
report that Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad has asked Indonesian
President Abdurrahman Wahid "to help foster closer Malaysian ties
with Israel."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister has never asked for assistance from the
Indonesian president or anybody else on the issue, Foreign
Minister Syed Hamid Albar told reporters here, referring to a
report in Far Eastern Economic Review's intelligence column of its
December 9 issue which said the prime minister had asked
Abdurrahman "to mediate" and "help foster closer Malaysian ties
with Israel,"according to Bernama news agency.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed the issue of Malaysia establishing relations with
Israel was never raised by the prime minister of Malaysia with
President Abdurrahman Wahid during the latter's visit to Malaysia
from November 6 to 7.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia takes strong objection to the remarks made by the
president if the report is true," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said if indeed Abdurrahman had made the statement, then
Malaysia took strong objection to it because Malaysia had never at
any time said anything to that effect.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministry had called the Indonesian Charge d'
affaires and expressed regret over the report and the Malaysian
ambassador in Jakarta had been told to call upon the Indonesian
foreign minister to convey Malaysia's stand.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister reiterated that Malaysia's position
towards Israel remained firm and the question of a third party
intervention did not arise.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia will not establish diplomatic or informal relations
with Israel until and unless a comprehensive solution to the
Middle East problem is achieved," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
