<HEADLINE> Grigorieva Clears Citizenship Hurdle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian-born pole vaulter
Tatiana Grigorieva has cleared a major obstacle in her bid to
compete for Australia at next year's Sydney Olympic Games,
according to reports from Adelaide, Australia.
</P>
<P>
Grigorieva had her Australian citizenship confirmed late Monday
after encountering problems meeting requirements that she complete
two uninterrupted years as a resident.
</P>
<P>
She won an appeal on the basis that husband and fellow Olympic
pole vaulting medal prospect Viktor Chistiakov was granted
citizenship earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Russia cleared the former unior hurdler to compete for
Australia but the clearance enabled her to represent Australia
only at certain events, such as this year's Seville world titles,
where she won a bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
The clearance did not allow her to represent Australia at the
Commonwealth or Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Chistiakov was granted citizenship earlier this year but
illness prevented him from competing at the world championships in
August.
</P>
<P>
Grigorieva and Chistiakov began training with Vitali Petrov,
former coach of the great Sergey Bubka, in Adelaide last month and
their manager Rick Carter said Petrov had agreed to coach them
through next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
