<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Attract More Asian Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is expected to
attract more tourists from Japan and the Republic of Korea (ROK)
next year, the East African newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Natural Resources and
Tourism Philemon Luhanjo was quoted as saying that the latest
marketing drive was expected to bring some 100,000 Japanese
tourists to Tanzania every year.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 10,000 Japanese and less than 5,000 people from the
ROK visit the country annually.
</P>
<P>
Mount Kilimanjaro, the highest peak in Africa and located in
the north of Tanzania, is the leading attraction for Japanese
tourists visiting East Africa, followed by wild life and nature
reserves.
</P>
<P>
Japan also funds the protected chimpanzee parks of Mahale and
Gombe in western Tanzania. Some 3,000 Japanese tourists visit the
two neighboring parks each year.
</P>
<P>
After President Benjamin Mkapa's visit to Japan and the ROK
last year, television crews from both countries visited Tanzania
and made documentaries about this country's tourism potential.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Tanzania played host to 482,331 tourists, who
brought in 501 million U.S. dollars in revenue. It is anticipated
that earnings from tourism could increase to 638 million dollars
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
