<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Hosts Regional Seminar on International Labor Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A three-day Asia Pacific
regional seminar on the application of the International Labor
Organization (ILO) Declaration on Fundamental Principles and
Rights at Work opened here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of representatives of governments, employers and
workers' organizations from more than 20 countries and regions are
participating in the seminar which was inaugurated by Prime
Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, organized by the Regional Office for Asia and the
Pacific of the International Labor Organization (ILO), will focus
on implementation of the principles contained in the ILO's
fundamental conventions, including the right to collective
bargaining, the elimination of forced labor and child labor and
anti-discrimination in employment.
</P>
<P>
The seminar will also discuss the ILO's latest convention, the
Worst Forms of Child Labor Convention, 1999, passed at the
International Labor Conference in June this year.
</P>
<P>
The new convention targets such practices as child slavery,
forced labor, trafficking, prostitution and various forms of
hazardous and exploitative work.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia has ratified all seven fundamental ILO conventions so
far this year, becoming the second in the region and the 48th
country in the world to do so. The Indonesian government last year
became the first in the region to do so.
</P>
<P>
The ILO estimated that, around the world, some 250 million
children between the ages of five and 14 work for a living. Almost
half, some 120 million, work full time, every day, all year round.
Of the 250 million, some 50 million to 60 million are between five
and 11 years old and work, by definition, in hazardous
circumstances considering their age and vulnerability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
