<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Malaysia Calls for Curbing Deforestation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund For
Nature (WWF) Malaysia Tuesday called on the authorities to curb
deforestation in the highlands and large-scale land clearing for
urban and agricultural development along the course of rivers.
</P>
<P>
WWF Malaysia Program Director K. Ramadasan Tuesday described
the deforestation as the main cause of flash floods that crippled
major roads in the Klang Valley (Kuala Lumpur and its surrounding
areas) and also triggered the landslide along the Tapah-Cameron
Highlands road in the northeast Monday.
</P>
<P>
The haphazard and the indiscriminate destruction of highlands
and wetlands in economic exploitation is an important element in
the aggravation of floods, he said in a statement here.
</P>
<P>
"Highland forests, which act as water sponges, have the ability
to slow down the flow of rain water down the slopes. It also
retains some of this water, regulating a more stable supply of
flow into the rivers," Ramadasan said.
</P>
<P>
He said wetlands also play an important role as they are able
to take up access water from a river during times of heavy
rainfall and act as a natural flood control mechanism.
</P>
<P>
He said once all these were destroyed, fast-flowing torrents of
water which are laden with eroded soil from slope surfaces will
find their way into streams and rivers contributing to floods,
especially in low-lying downstream areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
