<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Unveils Blueprint for Industrial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
announced a blueprint for industrial development to stimulate the
country's productive sectors.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Industry Iyorchia Ayu told a press briefing in
capital Abuja that the blueprint had set out the strategies for
action and time frame in the next four years for industrial
development, local media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister explained that the blueprint "will refocus the
policies of the government towards removing the problems and
constraints affecting the performance of the manufacturing
sub-sector and the productive sectors."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the present high level of import had remained the
bane of rapid industrialization in the country, describing as
"unfortunate and unacceptable" the current alarming rate of
import.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the unhealthy situation must be reversed
urgently in view of its dire consequences on employment
generation, domestic resource utilization, foreign exchange
resources and down stream industrial activities.
</P>
<P>
As a part of government efforts to stimulate domestic
production, Ayu said, the government has approved a tariff
structure that would favor import of machinery and raw materials
over finished goods with effect from the new year.
</P>
<P>
At the press briefing held on Monday, he stated that the
government had banned import of such goods as cement, sugar, pulp
and paper, plastics, petrochemicals, fish, cereals, chemicals and
rubber.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that conscious efforts were also being made to
resuscitate and rehabilitate some of ailing public companies like
the National Fertilizer Company, the Nigerian Sugar Company
Limited and the Federal Superphosphate Fertilizer Company.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that the government had approved the
establishment of a Cement Technology Institute with a view to
improving cement production in the West African country.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has directed the Nigerian National
Petroleum Corporation to make low pour fuel oil available to
cement companies at a cheaper rate and reduced the duties payable
by cement companies on their machinery and spare parts, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
