<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: New Century Calls for New World Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The approaching of the
21st century has added heat to the worldwide debate on how to
establish new world political and economic order. The most
frequently asked question is whether peace and stability will
prevail and the people, regardless of their race and nationality,
will be better off.
</P>
<P>
The answers are varied as hopes and worries mixed. The passing
century witnessed two world wars followed by the cold war. The
bitter experiences have made it reasonable to hope and seek for
the better. However, growing hegemony and power politics in the
post-cold war era have cautioned people against over-optimism. To
date, a new world order, eagerly hoped for by all, still seems to
remain on paper only.
</P>
<P>
With regard to a new world order, different countries have
different versions. When former U.S. President George Bush dished
out the U.S. idea in 1990, the U.S. lead was stressed. President
Bill Clinton underlined the same point as he outlined three
pillars of U.S. foreign strategy -- economy, security and
democracy. Pushing hard NATO's eastward expansion and cementing
ties with its Asian allies, the United States is in an obvious bid
to prevent potential adversaries from emerging and to maintain its
status as the only superpower in the world.
</P>
<P>
The endless bombing of Iraq and the U.S.-led NATO air strikes
against Yugoslavia without a mandate from the U.N. Security
Council have fueled doubts about what is really behind the U.S.
clamor about a new international order. Many countries believe
that the United States is pursuing a unipolar system, which goes
against their wish for a multipolar world. The new interventionism
advocated by the United States has been labeled by many developing
countries as "new hegemonism."
</P>
<P>
Desiring to be treated equally at the international arena,
developing countries share concerns with some European countries.
French President Jacques Chirac said early this year that no
single power should be allowed to monopolize world affairs. South
African Foreign Minister Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma has recently
called on developing countries to work together to build an all-
equally-involved world order.
</P>
<P>
"No one wants to challenge the U.S. status as superpower, and
in the meantime, no one wants to bow to the U.S. command," said
Professor Stephen M. Walt of John E. Kennedy School of Government,
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
Now, the debate has focused on how to nurture a new
international order, another divisive issue. Developed countries
led by the United States believe that the human rights issue
precedes sovereignty and that humanitarian intervention should not
be hindered by national borders. But developing nations fear that
the human rights situation in a country may be used by big powers
as a pretext to intervene in their internal affairs. Algerian
President Abdelaziz Bouteflika said at the September U.N. General
Assembly debate that "sovereignty is our final defense against the
rules of an unequal world."
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan said during the debate
that a just and reasonable new international order "should be
based on the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence, the purposes
and principles of the U.N. Charter and other universally-
recognized principles governing international relations." Russia
shared the stand, while some NATO members admitted that the 78-day
Kosovo military operation should not set a precedent.
</P>
<P>
All countries, big or small, rich or poor, have reached
consensus that the role of the U.N. should be enhanced in the next
century. President Clinton said at the U.N. General Assembly
debate that the role of the United Nations is "indispensable,"
urging Congress to pay more than 1 billion U.S. dollar dues to the
United Nations to save the U.S. prestige and the voting right at
the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Apart from its intention to peddle western policies and values
through the U.N., the United States needs the world body to deal
with international problems such as nuclear proliferation, drug
trafficking, organized crimes and environmental protection.
However, developing countries, for fear of missing the bandwagon
of globalization, want to have more say in world affairs.
</P>
<P>
Countries have failed to speak in one voice as to how to make
the U.N. function better. Complaints are getting louder about the
low efficiency of the U.N. Security Council and demands are
growing for further reform of the most powerful U.N. organ.
</P>
<P>
While Germany and Japan are striving for permanent seats at the
council, developing countries are calling for expanded
representation.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations should serve not only the big, but all
countries alike, said representatives from many countries at the
recent regional discussions on the agenda of the millennium summit,
scheduled for September 2000 in New York.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries have pinned their hope on the United
Nations for a larger share of tremendous benefit brought about by
globalization. Heavily indebted and with decreasing capital inflow,
they urge the United Nations to formulate fair and reasonable game
rules and elbowed developed countries to honor their aid
commitments and open their markets to commodities from developing
countries, in which 90 percent of the poor on the earth live.
</P>
<P>
There is no doubt that the existing world order must be
restructured, despite the process might be time-consuming. The
realization of the aspirations after peace, security and common
prosperity needs unrelenting efforts by people of several
generations and closer cooperation among nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
