<HEADLINE> Malaysian Military Urged to Conduct Joint Warfare Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian military has
been directed to place greater importance on conducting joint
warfare exercises involving the three services to upgrade the
joint capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Issuing the directive here Tuesday, Defense Minister Abang Abu
Bakar Abang Mustapha said such emphasis would serve as a good
gauge on the capabilities of the army, air force and the navy in
deploying and optimizing their resources.
</P>
<P>
He said that while preparations towards this end were already
in place, the new generation of officers of the tri-services would
have to keep themselves abreast with this requirement and trend.
</P>
<P>
The 21st century would see more complex military challenges
which require rearranging and redirecting the development of the
defense forces in safeguarding national interests, he said at a
function to present diploma to 152 graduates of the Armed Forces
Staff College here including 24 foreign military officers.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that plans to equip the Armed Forces Staff
College with new infrastructures would not be shelved despite the
lingering effects of the mid-1997 economic crisis on Malaysia's
defense modernization programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
