<HEADLINE> Foreign Organizations Accused of Launching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Majority leader of the Angolan
National Assembly Bornito de Sousa accused here on Tuesday some
foreign organizations of launching campaign against the Angolan
government, an official source has said.
</P>
<P>
Sousa criticized Global Witness, a British organization, for
having published a report accusing the Angolan government of its
bad management of public funds and demanding for "transparency" in
utilization of the money earned by the petroleum department.
</P>
<P>
The report, which has been rapidly diffused by the Portuguese
and the U. S. press, is an anti-government campaign, Sousa said,
stressing that Angola is a recognized country that should and
could use its resources for defending itself from any attack.
</P>
<P>
"Money for defense, health, education and other social areas is
part of the general budget of the country," said the lawmaker,
observing that the revenue in the petroleum industry is
significant for Angola's national income.
</P>
<P>
Sousa said the United States, Britain and Portugal also got
money from their national budget for supporting the war in the
Balkan area.
</P>
<P>
Revenue of the oil industry has been the top secret in Angola.
The second largest oil-producing country in Africa refused to
reveal the amount of the revenue even when negotiating with the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank for financial
assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
