<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Per-capita Financial Assets Up 27-Fold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's per-capita holdings
of financial assets showed a 27.3-fold rise over the past 19 years
due to price stability, diverse financial instruments and rising
incomes.
</P>
<P>
As of the end of June this year, per-capita financial assets
stood at 15.2 million won (13,200 U.S. dollars), compared with 556,
000 won in 1980, according to a report issued by the Bank of Korea
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During this period, the household sector's financial assets
registered an average year-on-year growth rate of 20.1 percent
while the sector's financial assets totaled 704.4 trillion won, or
1.6 times the nation's nominal gross national income and a 33.2-
fold jump from 21.2 trillion won in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of households' financial assets to aggregate
disposable income rose to 1.99 times in 1997 from 0.76 times in
1980.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, with household spending rising faster than the
savings rate, the growth of the accumulation level has been
slowing down since 1995.
</P>
<P>
In addition, financial assets accounted for 34.4 percent of
South Korean households' total wealth at the end of 1997 and
deposits at financial institutions accounted for 52.9 percent of
the sector's financial assets in June this year, up from 43.3
percent in 1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
