<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coal City Removes Its Chimneys to Control Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The coal city of Taiyuan in
north China's Shanxi Province has removed 212 chimneys over the
past five months in a major move to control heavy air pollution,
said mayor Cao Zhonghou.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of boilers have been targeted as the main culprits of
pollution in Taiyuan, one of the most polluted cities in the
country, and maybe even in the world.
</P>
<P>
Environment agencies said that boilers in the city emit more
than 13 million tons of dust, sulfur dioxide and other pollutants
every year.
</P>
<P>
The pollution caused by coking plants using outdated technology,
resulting in estimated economic losses of about 700 million yuan (
about 84 million U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
Pollution from Taiyuan, Linfen and other major cities in the
province have formed a massive pollution belt 200 kilometers long
and dozens of kilometers wide.
</P>
<P>
Various government departments in the city have introduced
environmentally-friendly furnaces and state-of-the-art technology
as well as using clean coal, gas, petroleum, electricity, solar
energy, and other new forms of energy. The government's goal is to
demolish 300 chimneys by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, the province, seeking cooperation in
pollution control, has contacted Germany, Austria, Norway, Canada,
the Netherlands, the United States, France, Japan and Britain, as
well as the Asian Development Bank (ADB).
</P>
<P>
Shanxi began to introduce foreign fund to start a waste water
treatment project in Yangquan City in 1994. Other cities like
Taiyuan and Changzhi have also cooperated with foreign countries
in environmental protection projects.
</P>
<P>
A United Nations environmental program supported by the World
Bank was launched in Taiyuan in March this year. By 2010 Taiyuan
hopes to comply with international standards of clean air.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
