<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Slightly Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks slid 95.53
points, or 0.59 percent, Tuesday to close at 16,073.09.
</P>
<P>
The dip, which occurred one day after the index soared to 16,
168.62 points, the first close above 16,000 since August 15, 1997,
was partly due to profit-taking, said analysts.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said the market was well-supported despite
the slide and the index will hover around 16,000 for a while.
</P>
<P>
They also said foreign cash will continue to flow into the
market of Hong Kong because many investors take Hong Kong as a
safe haven as the millennium approaches.
</P>
<P>
The turnover Tuesday was 12.89 billion Hong Kong dollars (1.65
billion U.S. dollars), 2 billion HK dollars (256 million U.S.
dollars) down from Monday's 14.89 billion HK dollars (1.91 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
All of the four sub-indices dropped, as Finance, Utilities,
Properties and Commerce &AMP; Industry fell 0.01 percent, 0.07 percent,
2.26 percent and 0.38 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index went down 1.77 percent
and Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corporations Index down 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stocks rose 22.34 points, or 0.14 percent, to open at
16,190.96 Tuesday and closed the morning session at 16,041.32.
</P>
</TEXT>
