<HEADLINE> Musharraf Pleads Pak-Iran Joint Efforts for Afghan Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Chief Executive
General Pervaiz Musharraf Tuesday advocated for joint strategy by
Pakistan and Iran to achieve "strategic objective" of peace in the
war-battered Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Strategic aims of the two countries are same "which is bringing
about peace in the region, bringing about peace in Afghanistan,"
the chief executive said in an interview with Iranian official
news agency IRNA in Rawalpindi, twin city of Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
General Musharraf is to embark on a two-day visit to Iran and
Bahrain on Wednesday for talks on international, regional and
bilateral issues.
</P>
<P>
Since he assumed the power after a bloodless coup on October 12,
General Musharraf, repeatedly in his policy statements, attached
much importance to promoting the bilateral relations with Iran,
which has kept lukewarm since the two neighbors chose to support
different warring factions in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is among the three countries which recognize Taliban
as the legal ruler of Afghanistan, however, Iran don't like
Taliban and is believed to be lending help to the anti-Taliban
opposition.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Iran, General Musharraf is scheduled to meet
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami and spiritual leader Seyed Ali
Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
"Pak-Iran common grounds are strategic. The modalities of
achieving that strategic objective of peace can be discussed and
we can have a common strategy," General Musharraf said, adding
that differences between Pakistan and Iran are monor.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a major difference because we have agreements in the
major areas. So the minor issues, the technical issues, as how to
bring about peace should be discussed like between two brothers
and we must agree to methodology to peace," he insisted.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan and Iran had excellent relations during the
Afghan Mujahiden (holy warrior) struggle against the erstwhile
Soviet invasion. "Therefore the relations should based on total
understanding," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he is sure that he will have "very detailed and heart-
to-heart talks" with Iranian leaders and they will "iron out
difference of opinion and have brotherly relations".
</P>
<P>
Besides renewing and establishing personal contacts with
Iranian leaders, General Musharraf said he will seek their support
for whatever happened in Pakistan. "That is the basis purpose," he
admitted.
</P>
<P>
Since the military takeover General Musharraf has visited a
number of Islamic countries to seek support for his new government.
</P>
</TEXT>
