<HEADLINE> New Meeting Between Palestinians, Israel Canceled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A new session of the transition
phase negotiations between the Palestinians and Israel, due to
have taken place Tuesday in Jerusalem, has been canceled, Voice
of Israel radio reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted a Palestinian source as saying that the
cancellation of the meeting is due to the failure of Monday's
meeting, at which the two parties could not bridge the gap regarding
the scheduled Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Visiting United States Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross
attended Monday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator for the transition phase talks
Saeb Erekat told Ross that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright should better shoulder the U.S. responsibility for the
implementation of the Sharm El Sheikh memorandum and putting an
end to Jewish settlement activity in the occupied territory.
</P>
<P>
Erekat presented Ross with a brief coverage of the issue of the
second redeployment of Israeli troops, involving withdrawal from 5
percent of the West Bank territory and the release of the third
group of Palestinian detainees in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed Ross on the Palestinian stance on the continued
Jewish settlement in the West Bank and the necessity of stopping
settlement activity.
</P>
<P>
Albright is due to begin her visit to Israel and the
Palestinian self-rule areas later Tuesday in an new bid to push
the peace process forward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
