<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference on Organized Crime to Be Held in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- An international conference on
judicial, banking and financial institutions fighting criminal
activities will be held at the Palais des Nations at Geneva on
December 9-10.
</P>
<P>
The conference will focus on the financial aspects of organized
crime, according to a press release here Tuesday by the United
Nations Economic Commission for Europe (UN/ECE).
</P>
<P>
Plenary sessions will concentrate on how governments can and do
react to organized crime, and how international institutions such
as the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the
Council of Europe can contribute to the fight against organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
The methods and proceedings of organized criminal groups, such
as money laundering, tax evasion, and corruption will be discussed,
and the situations in specific regions, including Africa, China
and Central and Eastern Europe will be elaborated.
</P>
<P>
Particular attention will be paid to the situation in Russia,
notably in the context of the privatization process and the
necessary transparency of this process.
</P>
<P>
The conference is organized by the Crans Montana Forum and the
Monaco World Summit under the auspices of the UN/ECE, the Council
of Europe, and the Supreme Court of France, with the cooperation
of the Center for Democracy and of the International Law Institute
in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
