<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Vows to Promote Irrigation in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada pledged Tuesday to continue to address farmers' irrigation
needs in Mindanao in a bid to transform the southern area into the
country's major food provider.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks during an ongoing visit to the
southern Philippine island.
</P>
<P>
He added that the National Irrigation Administration (NIA) will
continue to meet the needs in most parts of the area.
</P>
<P>
Mindanao, which accounts for more than 40 percent of the total
food trade of the country, is terribly short of irrigation and
more than half of the farm areas on the island lack it.
</P>
<P>
According to Estrada, the government will take care of the
irrigation need of this region and try to improve the service of
regional offices maintained there by the NIA.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Agriculture earlier reported to the president
the completion of 8,495 irrigation projects in various regions of
the country.
</P>
<P>
It added that the newly-completed projects are now servicing
some 200,000 national and communal irrigation systems nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary Edgardo Angara said the bumper rice and
corn harvests this year could be credited in part to the effective
irrigation program.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture sector is expected to grow 6 percent this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
