<HEADLINE> WTO Talks Failure Seen as Victory for Developing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has regarded the
abortive ministerial conference of the World Trade Organization
(WTO) in Seattle, the United States, last week as a victory for
developing countries, The Herald newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Industry and Commerce Nathan Shamuyarirai, who led
the Zimbabwean delegation to the conference, said Monday that the
collapse of the trade talks was also a warning that Africa should
be taken seriously at next year's negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He said developing countries, particularly those in Africa and
the Caribbean, had taken a strong position against the approach
employed by the developed countries and refused to budge.
</P>
<P>
The minister said developed countries wanted the WTO to waive
preferential trade arrangements for developing countries while the
latter were advocating for "special and differential treatment as
a fundamental principle of the multi-lateral trading system".
</P>
<P>
When the debate opened there were immediate differences between
 delegates from developed and developing countries on a wide range
of issues especially on agriculture, labour, dumping and market
access, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
