<HEADLINE> One Lebanese Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese civilian was killed
and two Syrian workers were wounded Tuesday morning during a
shelling on south Lebanon, the country's security sources said.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Daoud, 50, was killed instantly, and Salman Awad and Ali
Khalaf were moderately injured by shells when they were irrigating
an orchard near Mansouri village north of the Israeli occupied
border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
There has been no group claiming responsibility for the attack,
which raised the number of Lebanese civilians killed in south
Lebanon since the start of this year to 23. Another 150 were
wounded over the same period.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to
oust Israelis out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
