<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rowdyism Case Against Sharif Adjourned in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of Pakistan
Tuesday adjourned the hearing of a rowdyism case against the
deposed Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and others till January 12,
2000.
</P>
<P>
A 12-member bench, headed by Chief Justice Saeed-uz-Zaman
Siddiqui, directed the respondents to file objections against the
petitions till January 11, 2000.
</P>
<P>
From January 12, the court will take up the case on a day-to-
day basis.
</P>
<P>
The case had been admitted on a petition of freelance
journalist Shahid Orakzai and has been suspended for several
months.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary hearing of the case was held Tuesday amid
extraordinary security, with police clashing briefly with Pakistan
Muslim League (PML) workers outside the court building.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, head of the former ruling party PML, was specially
brought from Karachi, where he has been facing an attempted murder
and hijacking case, to attend the proceedings under a court notice.
Some other PML leaders were also accused in the rowdyism case.
</P>
<P>
When addressing the court, Sharif again complained of "inhuman
conditions" he has been supplied when in custody. He said that
since October 12, he has been treated as a common criminal.
</P>
<P>
On October 12, Sharif's government was dismissed in a bloodless
military coup and he was first under house arrest and then
formally arrested.
</P>
<P>
Khalid Anwar, law minister in Sharif's ousted government who is
representing the former prime minister, opposed the petitioner,
saying Orakzai is not an aggrieved party in the case.
</P>
<P>
The apex court barred Sharif from issuing any statement outside
the court. Entry to the building was restricted as no vehicle was
allowed to approach the building with police cordoning off the
area.
</P>
<P>
PML workers, including the party's members of parliament,
attacked the supreme court on November 28, 1997, when the then
Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah was hearing a contempt of court case
against Sharif.
</P>
<P>
In May 1999, a three-member bench of the supreme court has
acquitted all the PML legislators who were indicted on charges of
contempt of court for the attack due to its inability to give
specific evidence against them while proceedings against the
sitting prime minister were under way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
