<HEADLINE> U.N. Agency to Issue Environmental Report on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP) mission will present a report on preliminary
findings of environmental impact on the Republic of Guinea caused
by a large influx of refugees from Sierra Leone and Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The field mission Monday concluded the examining of the
problems of deforestation, erosion and unsustainable land use, the
issues of water and sanitation.
</P>
<P>
The team, sent to the western African country on November 24,
has so far undertaken pre-assessment work comprising a desk study
and field mission, according a news release issued by the
Nairobi-based UNEP Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Following an analysis of the preliminary assessment, the U.N.
environmental agency will make recommendations to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to determine actions to protect the
environment in Guinea.
</P>
<P>
When talking with Annan earlier this year, Guinean officials
expressed concern about the influx of refugees, now totalling some
450,000 into the forest areas close to the Guinean border. After
a request from Annan, the UNEP sent the mission to assess the
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
