<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, December 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The governments of Mexico and Spain signed here
on Monday the second protocol modifying the existing Treaty of
Extradition and Mutual Assistance in Penal Matters.
</P>
<P>
The document, signed by Mexican Attorney General Jorge Madrazo
and Spain's Justice Minister Margarita Mariscal de Gante Miron,
shows the two countries' desire to strengthen cooperation on the
fight against crimes, the Federal Attorney General's Office (PGR)
said in a communique. Mexico and Spain have kept in force the
Treaty of Extradition and Mutual Assistance in Penal Matters since
June 1, 1980. The first modifying was signed on June 23, 1999. (
Mexico-Spain-Extradition Treaty)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- The average price of OPEC's basket of seven crude
oils dropped slightly to 24.54 U.S. dollars per barrel last week
from 24.90 dollars in the previous week, the secretariat of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The average price per barrel in November reached 23.74 dollars,
the highest in recent months, compared with 21.67 dollars in
October. The price averaged only 12.28 dollars per barrel in 1998.
The continuous increase in oil prices strengthened OPEC's
determination to maintain the current production quota. Ali Al-n'
aimi, minister of petroleum and mineral resources of Saudi Arabia,
the main oil producer country of OPEC, said the oil price was
steady now and it was not necessary to change the current quota. (
Vienna-OPEC-Oil Price)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslavia's exports declined by 46.9 percent in
the first 11 months this year while its imports went down by 33.3
percent compared with the same period of last year, the newspaper
Politika reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Exports totaled 1.3 billion U.S. dollars while imports dropped
to 2.9 billion dollars in the period, as a result of the 78-day
airstrikes by the U.S.-led NATO earlier in the year. Exports and
imports in November went down by 16.1 and 55.5 percent from
October respectively. (Yugoslavia-Export)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- Representatives of China and Portugal on Monday
presented to the U.N. office in Vienna their governments'
statements on Macao's participation in the U.N. Commission on
Narcotic Drugs and the U.N. International Drug Control Program (
UNIDCP).
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese statement said that according to the 1987 Sino-
Portuguese Joint Declaration on the Question of Macao, the
Portuguese government's control over Macao's foreign affairs and
the territory's participation in the U.N. Commission on Narcotic
Drugs and the UNIDCP will cease on December 19, 1999. The Chinese
statement said that under the Sino-Portuguese joint declaration,
the Chinese government will resume the exercise of sovereignty
over Macao on December 20, 1999. From that day on, Macao will be
a special administrative region of China and the Chinese
government will be responsible for Macao's foreign affairs. (
Vienna-China-Portugal) 
</P>
</TEXT>
