<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB to Help Thailand Reform Budget System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) will help
Thailand improve and develop its government budget system, the
Thai News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
World Bank advisor to Thailand Sherrif Sayin was quoted as
saying on Tuesday that the Thai government's budget system is now
more standardized, compared with some other countries in the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
However, the government needs another three to five years to
improve and develop its budget system to meet the international
standard, where budgets of various governments, including those of
developed countries, could be compared and any faults could be
easily found and efficiently corrected, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government's budget system is based on cash, meaning
that debiting or crediting of accounts would be proceeded only
when there is any cash receipt or payment and thus causing
loopholes and leaks.
</P>
<P>
The new system would be based on a non-cash principle, enabling
it to help prevent and avoid any financial crisis in the future,
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Sayin said the World Bank considered that Thailand is now ready
to change its government budget system to be relevant to those of
developed countries and to meet the international standard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
