<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kashi to Become China's Largest Almond Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The far-western city of Kashi in
northwest China's Xinjiang Ugyur Autonomous Region aims to plant
10 million almond trees and become China's largest almond producer.
</P>
<P>
Almonds, introduced to Kashi more than 1,100 years ago, are
popular worldwide and sell well on the international market.
</P>
<P>
Thus far, the city has over 1 million almond trees, with output
exceeding 600,000 tons a year.
</P>
<P>
By 2001, the output value of Kashi's almond will reach 100
million yuan (12 million U.S. dollars), and the average per capita
income of farmers will be increased by 350 yuan (42 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Kashi, an important town on the ancient Silk Road, enjoys a lot
of sunshine and has a long frost-free period, with temperatures
varying greatly between day and night, suitable for the growth of
almonds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
