<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Singapore Strives for Innovation-Driven Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Singapore unveiled Monday an
ambitious 10-year blueprint aimed at maintaining a top workforce
and scoring a top-10 industry among the ranks of prominent
economic players in the world.
</P>
<P>
The new national productivity plan, or ProAct 21, is hoped to
usher in for the resources-poor state an innovation-driven economy,
or "a knowledge-based economy (KBE)," in the new century to
replace the current investment-based one.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1960s, Singapore has drawn up respective plans to
adapt itself to different phases in its economic development.
</P>
<P>
From the 1960s to the 1970s in a prevailing labor-driven
economy,the first development plan focused on job creation and
economic industrialization.
</P>
<P>
Later in the 1980s and the 1990s, as Singapore entered a
booming investment-driven era, the plan was revamped to stress
higher value-added activities.
</P>
<P>
The immediate results are eye-catching.
</P>
<P>
Over the last 18 years, productivity increases have contributed
more than half of the 7.2 percent average economic growth in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the standard of living in Singapore rose from 14,000
Singapore dollars (8,333 U.S. dollars) per person in 1980 to 31,
000 Singapore dollars (18,452 U.S. dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980, Singapore's workforce has been rated top by
Business Environment Risk Intelligence (BERI) and in terms of
industry and service, the city state was ranked 20th and 19th
respectively in the 1999 World Competitiveness Yearbook.
</P>
<P>
Singapore, however, can not afford to rest on its past laurels,
said Lee Suan Hiang, head of the Singapore Productivity and
Standards Board, when announcing the ProAct 21 Plan.
</P>
<P>
Through the new plan, Singapore strives to make itself one of
the world's 10 most productive countries in both manufacturing and
services by 2010 and its workforce the undisputed best.
</P>
<P>
Propelling forces behind the bold visions are eight strategic
thrusts in the fields such as mind-shaping, education, new
technology,pro-business environment, team-work upgrading, industry-
wide transformation and enterprise financing.
</P>
<P>
Among them, one of the major tasks is to inculcate a "new
productivity mindset" among its people and companies and equip
them with new tools and techniques to become more productive.
</P>
<P>
The plan will re-orientate workers toward innovation and value
creation rather than mere quality improvement and problem-solving.
</P>
<P>
The mindset change is "not just among the people but also
companies" because it poses the "greatest challenge" to Singapore'
s next productivity leap, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
A national productivity education program will be launched to
support the "mental revolution" needed for the KBE and as a
dynamic 10-year action plan, various initiatives and programs will
be unveiled over time, monitored by the PSB.
</P>
<P>
But Lee emphasized that ProAct 21 is not PSB's plan, but a
national blueprint, "a multi-agency approach that will involve
unions,employers and the government."
</P>
<P>
To survive and grow in the fast-changing economy, organizations
must build up their innovative capabilities and master the best
practices in managing their business, he said.
</P>
<P>
"With a world-class workforce and work-class organizations that
aim to stay ahead, Singapore will be well-placed for sustained
productivity and economic growth," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
