<HEADLINE> China Cuts Sulfur Dioxide Emissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- China has cut the emission of
sulfur dioxide by 1.3 million tons in nearly two years since
January 1998, a senior Chinese environmental protection official
said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the International Conference on Sulfur Dioxide
Pollution Control, Wang Xinfang, vice-director of China's State
Environmental Protection Administration, said the reduction has
helped improve the quality of air in 93 of 175 monitored cities.
</P>
<P>
To curb sulfur dioxide pollution, the Chinese central
government launched a campaign in January 1998 in designated
cities across China including Chongqing, Beijing, Shanghai,
Tianjin and other major cities in coastal areas and those listed
as key tourist destinations.
</P>
<P>
These designated areas are responsible for 60 percent of the
country's total sulfur dioxide emissions. Mines producing coal
with high sulfur content and small coal-powered power plants have
been shut down. Clean fuels such as natural gas, and clean
production have been encouraged and introduced.
</P>
<P>
Despite these efforts, China still faces a serious challenge in
resolving sulfur dioxide pollution as it is the largest coal
producer and consumer in the world, said the vice-director. To
make matters worse, China's annual output of coal with high sulfur
content reached 321 million tons last year, though this was 10
million tons less than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
China needs both financial and technological support to achieve
its sulfur dioxide control targets in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 400 people, including environmental protection officials
from both central and local governments and representatives from
environmental protection firms, will attended the three-day
conference which opened today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
