<HEADLINE> No New Tenders for Building of Settlements, Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
said Monday evening he does not expect the issuing of new
tenders for settlement construction in the occupied territories
while negotiations are under way with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Tel Aviv Tuesday morning said Barak
made the statements at a meeting with a number of activists of his
Labour party.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister pointed out that issuing new tenders will
harm Israel's prestige worldwide and will damage negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat
threatened, on the eve of the arrival in Israel Tuesday of United
States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, to suspend final
status negotiations should the Barak government continue to expand
Jewish settlements in the Palestinian territory.
</P>
<P>
According to Arafat's adviser Nabil Shaath, Arafat, in the
course of his recent meeting in the West Bank city of Ramallah
with U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis Ross, called for U.S.
intervention to rescue the final status negotiations from collapse
due to Israeli settlement activity.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator for final status talks Yasser Abed
Rabbo announced after the 8th session of final status talks Monday
that his side will not proceed with the talks until Israel stops
expanding settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Monday's negotiations hit a snag as the Palestinian delegation
refused to discuss the issue of Palestinian refugees, which was
tabled for consideration at the session, and demanded a discussion
of the settlement issue instead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
