<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Turn Deserts Into Vegetated Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- China announced today that it
will stem its vast deserts, mostly in the western areas, from
expanding within 10 years and make a major bid to turn the
floating sands into vegetated land.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Liming, a State Forestry Administration (SFA) official in
charge of desert control, said that a total of 1.69 million square
kilometers of desert or desertified land in 14 provinces and
autonomous regions will be involved in the project.
</P>
<P>
Of the total figure, planting grass and trees will be feasible
on about 530,000 square kilometers of desert, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
China plans to improve 24.6 million ha of desertified land and
plant grass and trees on 15.3 million ha of land over the next 10
years. The upper reaches of the Yangtze and Yellow River valleys
which have vast arid areas of deserts will be slated for
vegetation.
</P>
<P>
Desert control and treatment will be a major part of China's
strategy to accelerate economic development in its mammoth western
areas, said Li Yucai, deputy director of the SFA, who added that
China will earmark 100 billion yuan for a massive afforestation
campaign within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
China has 2.62 million square kilometers of desertified land.
Ever-expanding desert sprawls at an annual rate of 2,000 square
kilometers. Sandstorms brings about direct economic losses of 8.4
billion yuan annually.
</P>
<P>
China began the fight against desertification as early as in
the 1950s. A comprehensive attempt at controlling China's deserts
was launched in later 1980s. To date, 160,000 square kilometers of
wasteland covered with floating sand, or one-tenth of the
desertified land in China, has been turned into arable land or
forested zones, Li said.
</P>
<P>
A desert expert from the Chinese Academy of Sciences said China
has developed a series of techniques to control its desert
including aerial seeding and growing paddy rice fields on arid
areas by lining 20-centimeter deep furrows with plastic cover for
preserving both water and nutrients.
</P>
<P>
An official with the United Nations Environment Program (UNEP)
said that China leads the world in desert control techniques.
</P>
<P>
By 2050, China will expand its forest areas by 74.5 million ha
and bring 66 million ha of its desert under control by planting
trees and grasses, Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Police Chief Confident of Macao Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Macao, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Chen Shaoji, director of the
Provincial Public Security Bureau of Guangdong, expressed his
confidence in the security of Macao during the period of the
handover ceremony, due on December 20, and celebrations.
</P>
<P>
"The homecoming of Macao has drawn worldwide attention and is
the aspiration of the Chinese people," Chen said, adding that
anyone who attempts to make trouble would be "enemy of the people
and the state,"and would be denounced by people from all circles.
</P>
<P>
Chen made the remarks after attending the 33rd regular meeting
between top police officers from Guangdong and Macao. Chen and
Manuel Soares Monge, secretary for security of the Portuguese
Macao government,met this morning to sum up the experience of the
Guangdong-Macao police cooperation this year.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that this year, especially in recent months,
Guangdong and Macao police departments have made the biggest-ever
achievements in security and border control. Special progress has
been seen in cracking down on sneaking and organized crime.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have set up an increasingly effective mechanism
of information exchange, it is learned.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Macao side spoke highly of the efforts
made by the Guangdong police in battling sneakers and criminal
rings and disclosed that thanks to the crackdowns by Guangdong
police, the number of illegal entries into Macao has declined
markedly.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached an agreement that during the handover
period,Macao police would be responsible for security issues in
the territory while Guangdong police would spare no efforts to
support Macao police in their efforts.
</P>
<P>
A round-the-clock hot-line will be set up to ensure speedy and
effective coordination between the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
