<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Review of International Situation in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
December 7, Beijing (Xinhua) -- The year 1999 witnessed a spate
of striking events and developments throughout the world. Fresh
developments of hegemonism and power politics, together with an
escalation of local wars and regional conflicts, further
complicated international relations and the world's security
situation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) created
a dangerous precedent of willfully interfering with the internal
affairs of other countries and invading a sovereign state in its
78-day bombardment against Yugoslavia on March 24. The ethnic
conflicts in Kosovo belong to the internal affairs of Yugoslavia
and should be settled through consultations by the various ethnic
groups. The international community can initiate dialogues on the
issue to help seek solutions.
</P>
<P>
NATO, however, launched massive air raids on Yugoslavia without
a mandate of the United Nations, inflicting suffering upon the
Yugoslav people and incurring strong condemnations from peace-
loving and justice-seeking people of different countries. In a
barbarous move, the military bloc also attacked the Chinese
embassy in Yugoslavia, arousing extreme indignation among the
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The invasion against Yugoslavia was in essence a trial made by
the U.S.-led western powers of NATO's new concept. The concept on
the one hand is to pursue eastward expansion and on the other hand
to extend its defense scope beyond NATO, as exemplified by its
armed intervention in Yugoslavia's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
NATO's new concept is an important part of the U.S. global
strategy. Its goal is to maintain its status in the 21st century
as the sole super power that plays a dominant and leading role in
international affairs. The endeavor has been exposed by
international consensus as the U.S. attempts to create a unipolar
system.
</P>
<P>
At home, the United States sought to maintain an absolute
predominance in military technologies by developing its national
strategic defense system. In Europe, the United States reinforced
NATO in a bid to achieve its double aim of controlling its
European allies on the one hand and squeezing Russia's strategic
space on the other.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, the United States strengthened its defense cooperation
with Japan. In the meantime, it jointly conducted research and
development on the Theater Defense Missile system with Japan and
others. The moves have made Asian countries highly alert and upset.
In Latin America, the United States adjusted its policies toward
the region and is now working to create a sweeping American market
to stabilize its backyard. In the Middle East, it insisted on the
continuation of peace talks between Israelis and Palestinians
while trying to suppress Iraq and some other countries. In Africa,
the Untied States expanded its influence by cementing its economic
bonds with African nations.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo war caused big countries to grow sharp on their
differences and conflicts, and harmed their partnership building
efforts. The world disarmament process suffered setbacks as a
result. The question of military security has once again drawn
wide attention.
</P>
<P>
The United States not only led the aggressive war against
Yugoslavia but also drastically increased its spending on anti-
missile defense in a bid to seek nuclear predominance. Its attempt
will force other countries to increase their military expenditures
and may also trigger an arms race in outer space.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate's refusal to ratify the Comprehensive Nuclear
Test Ban Treaty in October and the country's threat to quit the
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty showed that it ran counter to the
general disarmament efforts in the world. What added to the unease
of the international community was the missile test-fire race
between India and Pakistan and their subsequent military conflicts
over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
An array of events that occurred during the year revealed that
the continued existence of factors that could disturb the local or
regional situations. Russia's fight against Chechen rebel forces,
relaxation of conflicts in mid-Africa, the break-off of the
deadlock on Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, the development of
the situation in East Timor, the general election in Indonesia and
the coup in Pakistan can serve as examples.
</P>
<P>
Economically, the world emerged from the adverse impact of
financial turmoils and embarked on the track of continued growth.
The International Monetary Fund predicted a 3.5 percent growth
rate for the global economy, higher than the 2.5 percent of last
year. The U.S. economy maintained its growth momentum and the
euroland economy has been back on the track of recovery, while
South Korea and Southeast Asian nations have lifted themselves out
of the valley of crisis faster than had been expected.
</P>
<P>
However, there are still hidden dangers in the world economy,
particularly the bubbles in the U.S. stock market and the
worldwide low customer demand. Lessons from the financial crises
should be well taken.
</P>
<P>
With the continued development of economic globalization and
regionalization, the economic links between nations and regions
have grown more extensive and closer. How to guarantee the
economic security in the process of economic globalization has
become a significant subject for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The world pattern, composed of one super power, several major
powers, some developed small and medium-sized nations plus the
broad range of developing nations, has undergone no significant
changes. The trend toward multipolar system is still growing.
Historical experiences have demonstrated that any attempt to
monopolize the world is doomed to failure. All powers must get the
support of relevant nations if they wish to solve global or
regional issues.
</P>
<P>
As all nations map out their strategies on the basis of their
own interests in efforts to seek development and occupy vantage
points in international competitions, friction and even disputes
are unavoidable. Development can be secured only in relatively
stable international environment. Dialogues and consultations are
the only way to secure a relative balance. It is hoped that all
conflicts can be settled through various mechanisms of
consultations while upholding justice and fairness, opposing war
and safeguarding peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
