<HEADLINE> Foreign Currencies Shortage Hits Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has been hit by a
shortage of foreign exchange, especially the U.S. dollars, raising
concerns among the business community about the falling kwacha,
Times of Zambia newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The kwacha has tumbled from 2,550 to 2,700 against one dollar
since last Thursday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
George Chabwera, chairman of the Zambia Association of Chambers
of Commerce and Industry, Monday described the situation as
regrettable and called for the intervention of the central bank.
</P>
<P>
"The kwacha is reacting to the normal rule of demand and
supply. It is also a sign of the economy not being productive.
Businesses that depend on inputs like imported raw materials are
the ones that suffer most," he said.
</P>
<P>
He observed that the only remedy was for the Bank of Zambia
(BOZ) to intervene and increase the capacity of foreign exchange
earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
