<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 07:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beirut Listed Among World's Most Expensive Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations survey on the
cost of living in 183 cities has put Lebanese capital Beirut among
the most expensive cities around the world.
</P>
<P>
The study, which covered all the countries where the UN has
offices, ranked Beirut as the 22nd-most expensive city in the
world, the Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
New York, which ranked 14th with 100 points, is only three
points ahead of Beirut, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong of China, Tokyo of Japan and Tripoli of Libya were
ranked as the three most expensive cities.
</P>
<P>
The study, which covered the prices of basic commodities
and housing prices, did not include the level of wages.
</P>
<P>
Beirut was also ranked as the second-most expensive city in
the Middle East after Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicated Beirut was the most expensive tourist
destination in the Arab world and was seven points ahead of Cairo,
which is considered the biggest tourist destination in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
Many Lebanese blamed the high cost of living for the growing
prices of electricity, customs, labor costs and social-security
tax.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Ashqar, president of the country's hotel syndicate,
rejected the notion that hotels in Lebanon were the most
expensive in the world.
</P>
<P>
"We pay expensive power, high customs and 37 percent tax
to cover the social security of staff and yet our prices
are almost the same as many regional countries," he claimed.
</P>
</TEXT>
