<HEADLINE> Settlement of Kashmir Issue Key to Pakistan-India Ties: President (RPT) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Rafiq
Tarar has said that the settlement of the Jammu and Kashmir issue
is crucial to the normalization of bilateral relations between
Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
"It should be clear to everyone that without resolving the core
issue of Kashmir, normalization of relations between Pakistan and
India will remain a dream," he said while addressing the annual
Banquet of the Association of Retired Ambassadors here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There exist many problems between India and Pakistan, of which
the core issue is that of Kashmir."
</P>
<P>
Since the nuclear tests by India and Pakistan last year, he
said, the world perceived Kashmir issue as a nuclear flashpoint
and "is anxious to promote nuclear restraint as well as confidence-
building measures."
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan is keen to resume a meaningful and result-
oriented dialogue with India. "We trust that this process will be
revived in the near future."
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Pakistani Foreign Minister Abdul Sattar
said Pakistan is ready to have talks with India on the basis of
agreements already reached between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions from journalists, he said Pakistan is ready
for a dialogue with India "in pursuance of the agreements."
</P>
<P>
The banquet was also attended by diplomats from many countries.
</P>
