<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Industrial Output Value Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's industrial production
value reached 153.13 trillion Vietnamese dong (10.9 billion U.S.
dollars) in the first 11 months of this year, a year-on-year
increase of 10.3 percent, Vietnam News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the figure, 67 trillion (4.78 billion dollars) came from
state-owned enterprises, 33 trillion dong (2.36 billion dollars)
from non-state enterprises, and the remaining 53 trillion dong (3.
78 billion dollars) from foreign-invested enterprises, making year-
to-year increases of 5, 8.5 and 19.4 percent respectively,
according to the General Statistics Office.
</P>
<P>
High growth rates were recorded in the country's industrial
centers, 27 percent in Binh Duong province, 23 percent in Ba Ria-
Vung Tau province, 15.3 percent in Dong Nai province and 10
percent in Ho Chi Minh City, in southern Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Industrial products that registered high growth rates were
crude oil, aquatic products, garments, rolling steel and
electricity.
</P>
<P>
However, some items experienced year-to-year declines, such as
anthracite, electric motors and machinery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
