<HEADLINE> Newspaper Publishes List of Tax-Evading Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A newspaper in Shenyang,
capital of northeast China's Liaoning Province, has published a
list of 173 enterprises that failed to pay their due taxes.
</P>
<P>
This is part of a punishment adopted by the Liaoning Taxation
Bureau, according to Zhao Shichun, director of the bureau.
</P>
<P>
The names of the enterprises' chief executives were also listed
in Shenyang Daily last week. The taxes owed by these enterprises
totaled over 30 million yuan (3.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The amount of taxes they owed ranges from a mere 100 yuan (12
dollars) to more than 5 million yuan (600,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
"No matter how small the amount, the nature of owing taxes is
the same," Zhao emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Freezing capital and assets and auctioning properties are also
among the measures adopted to punish tax-evasion and delays in
paying tax, he added.
</P>
<P>
These measures are aimed at raising the enterprises' awareness
of their obligation to pay taxes and to protect state interest, he
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
