<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Oil Reserves Reach 8.89 Billion Barrels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's national petroleum
reserves stood at 8.89 billion barrels as of January 1, 1999 while
natural gas reserves were 133.35 trillion cubic feet, an official
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Up to now, we have explored as much 38 basins from 60 sediment
basins which we have," Director Martiono Hadianto of the state-run
oil and gas company, Pertamina, said at the parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia's oil production capacity could still be
maintained and even increased in a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
"(Production capacity can be increased) As long as the
international oil price could be held at a high level and the
government is able to push exploration activities to find new
reserves," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is one of the members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
Currently oil price in the international market is 25 U.S
dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
At present, he said, Indonesia's petroleum output comes from
the country's western area.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore in the third millennium the development of oil and
gas industries will be directed to the eastern territory, moreover
we have found new oil reserves in the Malaka Straits and Irian
Jaya," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hadianto added that Indonesia has also a great potential for
developing geothermal energy.
</P>
<P>
"We have identified about 70 fields of geothermal energy whose
potential is estimated at about 19.658 megawatts," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
