<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meretz Threatens to Quit Israeli Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli party of Meretz
has threatened to quit the coalition if the government continues
its policies of settlement expansion, land expropriations,
deportations and home demolitions against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"Meretz can only accept responsibility for government decisions
if it is a partner to such decisions," which is often not the
case, Meretz party leader Yossi Sarid said on Monday at a Knesset
faction meeting, the Jerusalem Post reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meretz's threat to quit the government followed Monday's
decision by the Palestinians not to continue with peace talks
until Israel stops settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the Housing Ministry issued tenders for building
another 500 houses for settlers in the West Bank, bringing the
total tenders issued by the current government to 3,196 since it
came to power in July.
</P>
<P>
The Housing Ministry said the tenders were approved by Prime
Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
At Monday's Meretz faction meeting, Sarid, also Education
Minister, condemned the recent evacuation of palestinian
cave--dwellers near Yata near Hebron, saying the evacuation was
one of the most ugly and contemptible of the old Israeli
occupation policies in the territories.
</P>
<P>
"Meretz isn't sitting in the government in order to lend
a hand to such things that it would never agree to," Sarid
said.
</P>
<P>
Urging the Palestinians to return to the negotiating table,
State Department Spokesman James Rubin told reporters on the
plane en route to Riyadh Monday night that the United States
believes the Palestinians should not make "preconditions" by
linking the final-status talks to the halting of Israeli
settlement activities in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But Rubin also made it clear that the U.S. sees
settlement expansion as "unhelpful" and it can "harm the
environment in which the peace process has to take place."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
