<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Engineers Sentenced for Major Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Two railway engineers who were
found guilty of causing a major train accident on the Beijing-
Guangzhou Railway Line in July were sentenced last weekend to
prison terms of six months and one year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The ruling was handed down by the Hengyang Railway Transport
Court of central China's Hunan Province in an open trial held on
December 4.
</P>
<P>
Li Jingcheng and Zhang Hong were both engineers with the
Changsha Maintenance Section of the Changsha Railways Corporation.
On July 9, the two, with Li as the chief engineer and Zhang as co-
engineer, were towing the Wuchang-Zhanjiang 461 Train from
Changsha to Hengshan by locomotive at about 11 o'clock at night.
</P>
<P>
The two failed to apply the brakes and reduce their high speed
of 111 km per hour in time while passing a turnoff near Hengyang,
which allows for a speed of only 45 km per hour. This failure
resulted in derailment of the train.
</P>
<P>
The accident killed nine people, injured 40 others, and
destroyed 12 carriages, causing direct economic losses of over six
million yuan. Because of the accident, railway transport
operations heading south on the major north-south Beijing-
Guangzhou trunk line were completely suspended for more than 32
hours.
</P>
<P>
At Saturday's trial, Li Jingcheng and Zhang Hong were both
found guilty of committing a railway operation safety crime. Li
was sentenced to one year's imprisonment and Zhang was given a six-
month prison sentence. The two were both given one year's
probation in consideration of their cooperative attitude with
accident investigators.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
