<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Huge Inkstone to Honor Macao's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A master craftsman in
north China have made a 26-ton inkstone to honor the upcoming
return of Macao to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The inkstone is 6.3-meters long, 2.6-meter-wide and 1.2-meters
high taken from a 60-ton rock from a mountain along the Yishui
River in Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Yishui inkslabs, which are very famous for their exquisiteness,
rank among one of the four best kinds of inkstones in China.
</P>
<P>
The artwork on the inkstone bears 1999 lotus in full blossom,
12 phoenix and 20 dragons, and auspicious signs marking the Macao'
s return to the motherland on December 20. Macao has been
subjected to foreign colonial rule for more than 100 years.
</P>
<P>
Ma Jingwen, a well-known craftsman, said that inkstone and
swallow are both pronounced as "Yan" in the Chinese language. A
swallow flying home symbolizes the return of Macao.
</P>
<P>
It was no easy feat for local workers to move the rock from
the mountain. Initially, workers attempted to move the 60-ton
stone onto a 10-ton truck with little success. They then laid down
logs on the ground and moved the rock little by little to the
Hebei Yishui Carving Center. During the process two bridges were
damaged.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of skilled craftsmen have spent more than two years
completing the inkslab.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, U.S. Discuss Congo Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe has held talks with Richard Holbrooke, ambassador of the
United States to the United Nations, on the peace process in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters after the meeting which took more than two
hours here on Monday, Holbrooke said they discussed how the U.S.
could help in the effective implementation of the Lusaka pace
accord which was signed in July and August this year by the
warring parties to the DRC conflict.
</P>
<P>
"We were here to understand first before we are able to make
decisions," said U.S. senator Russell Feingold who was
accompanying Holbrooke on his African tour.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports of renewed fighting in the DRC, with
both sides accusing each other of violating the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke could not give details about the meeting, but he and
his party expressed the concern about the renewed fighting in the
DRC, which threatens to tear the Lusaka accord apart.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs Susan
Rice told reporters last month that her country was prepared to
offer material and financial support to end the conflict.
</P>
<P>
She said the U.S. supported three main components of the Lusaka
accord, namely the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the
DRC, withdrawal of foreign troops and the democratic transition of
the central African country.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
