<HEADLINE> SW China City to Plant More Bamboo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The city of Chishui in
southwest China's Guizhou Province plans to return 22,800 ha of
farmland to bamboo forest in the next three years, and its bamboo
forest area is expected to reach 108,433 ha by 2001.
</P>
<P>
Chishui is one of the country's ten major bamboo-growing areas,
and currently has 60,241 ha of bamboo forest, ranking first in
southwest China.
</P>
<P>
The city has used 15 million yuan (1.8 million U.S. dollars) in
loans from the World Bank to renovate the low-yielding bamboo
forest.
</P>
<P>
Concurrently, the city will focus effort on developing bamboo-
related products and aims to become the largest bamboo processing
base in southwest China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
