<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Asia to See Steady Growth in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- If the faster-than-expected
economic recovery in Asia this year proves a beginning of a
cyclical upswing, then the region is likely to see strong and
steady growth in 2000.
</P>
<P>
With a financial crisis drawing to an end, Asia's performance
in 1999 is extremely remarkable. The gross domestic product (GDP)
growth rate for Southeast Asia is projected to be 3 percent this
year, in sharp contrast with a negative growth of 7.5 in 1998,
according to a forecast by the Asian Development Bank (ADB) in
November.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, which suffered a 5.8 percent GDP decrease a year
ago, could register a 9 percent growth this year, and Singapore,
Thailand, the Philippines and Malaysia follow South Korea with
growth in the range of 3 percent to 5 percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The developing Asia will register an average growth rate of 5.
7 percent this year from 2.3 percent in 1998, and all these
countries are expected to maintain the same growth rate in 2000,"
the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Asia's recovery this year has been based on an increase in
global demand for electronic products, an increase in commodity
prices and a strengthening domestic demand as a result of
reflationary monetary and fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
The fast turnaround, which started in the first quarter of the
year, has set the stage of for a more robust growth in 2000,
economists said.
</P>
<P>
Also, conditions for economic growth in 2000 appear more
favorable than this year.
</P>
<P>
After two years of belt-tightening, consumers in the region are
starting to spend again. More consumption will inevitably
stimulate demand of the domestic market and eventually lead to
economic expansion in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Once more, consumers are spending, despite unemployment
concerns. Retail sales are soaring, including sales of durable
items such as cars," said Manu Bhaskaran, managing director and
group head of research at SG Securities in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"Thais and (South) Koreans, among others, are digging deep into
their pockets for more expensive items, suggesting their long-term
view of the economic future has improved substantially," he said.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that a rise in consumption would also help ease
the deflationary pressure in some Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
With investor confidence returning, the increasing inflows of
private capital into Asia could fuel the steady growth next year,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Recent data shows that net private capital inflows to the five
crisis-affected countries -- Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand, the
Philippines, and South Korea -- are forecast to rise to 5.1
billion U.S. dollars in 1999 as opposed to a net outflow of 38.6
dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
More foreign capital inflows into the region are almost certain
in 2000, after the initial increase this year, economists said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the recent resurgence of loan growth could
gradually loosen a painful constraint on economic recovery in Asia
next year.
</P>
<P>
In a report published last month, Roy Ramos, a regional banking
analyst at Goldman Sachs, said that "loan growth has started to re-
emerge on a month-on-month basis across Asia" and in some cases is
giving rise to"surprisingly robust annualized growth rates."
</P>
<P>
In Malaysia, new loan approvals almost doubled in the first
nine months of this year. Even in Thailand, some of the surviving
domestic banks are talking about increasing their loan portfolio
by about 4 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
What is most important for Asia to achieve a steady growth next
year is a much better social and political environment in the
region now.
</P>
<P>
From Indonesia to South Korea, from Thailand to the Philippines,
the easing of economic difficulties in the past year has made the
political and social environment more conducive to the economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
Such a trend is expected to continue in the coming year and
help Asian countries to concentrate on economic development,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
However, in the new year, reform efforts need to be sustained
if the growth momentum is to be maintained and social costs of any
future downturns are to be minimized.
</P>
<P>
This is the advice for Asian economies by the Manila-based ADB.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
