<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangkok Bank to Apply New Rating System to Control Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's largest commercial
bank, Bangkok Bank, will apply a new rating system for borrowers
over the next three years as part of a new risk management scheme,
the Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new rating scheme would be used by the bank internally in
calculating how to price risks and set interest rates for
borrowers, Ayuth Krishanamara, Bangkok Bank executive vice
president, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
But first of all, the bank wants to build up its information
database on borrowers, including business plans and cashflow
projections.
</P>
<P>
At present, the bank's interest rates for loans are based on
minimum lending or minimum retail rates plus a premium based on
risks faced by different industries.
</P>
<P>
The new system would allow the bank to offer good customers
lower interest rates, reflecting their lower credit risks, Ayuth
said.
</P>
<P>
Lending practices by the bank will change completely. Prime
focus will be given on borrowers' capacity to service their debt,
their operational procedures, technology, management practices and
accounting procedures.
</P>
<P>
Borrowers not in line with the bank's standards will go through
a screening process on what risks are present and how they should
be managed and priced.
</P>
<P>
By taking a more systematic approach, old practices of
relationship-based lending will be reduced.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Bank ranked among the world's most profitable in 1993,
but since July 1997 it has become one of the most troubled. It
posted a loss of 1.4 billion U.S. dollars in 1998. Of its loans
totaling 958 billion baht (25 billion dollars), half are
classified as non-performing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
