<HEADLINE> Cellular Phone Sales to Set Record in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's mobile phone
industry is going to see a boom as an estimated one million
handsets are expected to be sold this year, the Nation newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the total handsets sold, 60 percent were purchased by first-
time subscribers, while the rest were picked up by existing
subscribers moving up to newer models, the newspaper quoted
information provided by suppliers and mobile phone operators.
</P>
<P>
Giant international suppliers all benefit from the boom, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The sales of Nokia mobile phones, which has taken more than
half of the local market, had reached their peak, the company said,
without giving details of sales volume.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's Ericsson and the U.S.-based Motorola also enjoyed good
sales performance this year. Ericsson said it has sold around 250,
000 handsets this year.
</P>
<P>
The soaring demand for mobile phones is also encouraging
network operators to work out network expansion plans to serve the
greater number of subscribers in the new century.
</P>
<P>
Advanced Info Service (AIS), the country's largest mobile phone
operator,allocated 10 billion baht (259.7 million U.S. dollars)
for its expansion project next year, while its two rivals also set
aside four billion baht (103.8 million dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
AIS said it is expected to see 360,000 new subscribers this
year,making the company's total subscribers 1.2 million by the end
of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
