<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Portugal on Macao's Role in U.N. Narcotics Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of China and
Portugal on Monday presented to the U.N. office in Vienna their
governments' statements on Macao's participation in the U.N.
Commission on Narcotic Drugs and the U.N. International Drug
Control Program (UNIDCP).
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese statement said that according to the 1987 Sino-
Portuguese Joint Declaration on the Question of Macao, the
Portuguese government's control over Macao's foreign affairs and
the territory's participation in the U.N. Commission on Narcotic
Drugs and the UNIDCP will cease on December 19, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese statement said that under the Sino-Portuguese joint
declaration, the Chinese government will resume the exercise of
sovereignty over Macao on December 20, 1999. From that day on,
Macao will be a special administrative region of China and the
Chinese government will be responsible for Macao's foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
It said China's membership in the U.N. Commission on Narcotic
Drugs shall cover Macao as of December 20, 1999. Accordingly, the
Chinese government acknowledges that as of December 20, 1999,
representatives of the Macao Special Administrative Region should
be able to continue to attend plenary sessions and special
meetings of the U.N. Commission on Narcotic Drugs and other drug-
related international conferences in the capacity of Chinese
representatives.
</P>
<P>
While respecting regulations of the U.N. Commission on Narcotic
Drugs, the Macao Special Administrative Region, with the
permission of the Chinese government, should be able to
participate independently, in the name "Macao, China", in Asia-
Pacific anti-narcotic executives' meetings and continue to
participate in relevant activities of the UNIDCP.
</P>
<P>
According to relevant international conventions, Macao's
reports on narcotic and psychotropic drugs should first be sent to
the central government of China which will then transfer them to U.
N. agencies, the Chinese statement said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese representative to the U.N. and other international
organizations in Vienna, Zhang Yishan, in a note to the U.N.
office in Vienna, asked its director Pino Arlacchi to put China's
statement on record and call the attention of all members of the U.
N. narcotic commission to it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
