<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Snuff out Fake Cigarettes Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The business of making and
selling fake and substandard cigarettes in China is about to go up
in smoke, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The State Quality and Technical Supervision Administration has
launched a nationwide, iron-fisted crackdown on manufacturers and
distributors of shoddy cigarettes. Officials say they want to
restore market order and better protect consumers' rights.
</P>
<P>
In a single crackdown last week in Guizhou Province, officials
seized more than 2,000 cartons of cigarettes with forged
trademarks, 53 manufacturing machines, tons of tobacco leaves and
packing materials, the administration said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Production and sales of fake and substandard cigarettes have
run rampant in eastern and southern provinces such as Fujian and
Guangdong in recent years, despite crackdowns launched every year.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale action will also be launched in Guangxi, Hainan,
Zhejiang, Beijing and Shanghai, which are known as prime spots for
the manufacturing and sales of fraudulent tobacco products, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Some manufacturers and distributors have even set up complete
networks across the country to dodge crackdowns.
</P>
<P>
They evade about 10 billion yuan (about 1.2 billion U.S.
dollars) in taxes every year through illegal production and sales
of such cigarettes, said Pan Yue, a senior administration official.
</P>
<P>
Domestic manufactures of brand-name cigarette products also
suffer grave economic losses from the scam, Pan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
