<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada in Memory of Victims of Montreal Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada staged national memorial
services Monday to mark the 10th anniversary of Montreal massacre,
which killed 14 women.
</P>
<P>
In Ottawa, Prime Minister Jean Chretien paid tribute to the
victims with the capital city flying the national flag at half
mast.
</P>
<P>
"Time stood still in Canada on that day and for the families
and friends of the 14 victims who were taken by this act of insane
rage," the prime minister said at Parliament Hill.
</P>
<P>
In Montreal, a plaque with the 14 victims' names was unveiled
at the Ecole Polytechnic School, the scene where the massacre took
place.
</P>
<P>
A 25-year-old gunman shot and killed 14 female students and
employees and injured 13 others in an anti-feminist shooting spree
on December 6, 1989. The gunman shot himself dead after the
shooting spree.
</P>
<P>
Montrealer Jim Edward was shedding tears Monday for his
daughter Anne-Marie, one of the 14 women killed by the deranged
gunman. He and his wife were among several hundred people turning
out in pouring rain for a memorial service at the Ecole
Polytechnic School.
</P>
<P>
Memorial services were also witnessed in other major Canadian
cities including Edmonton and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
The massacre led to a registry and licensing system for
firearms owners in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
