<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia's Foreign Trade declines in First 11 Months of 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia's exports declined
by 46.9 percent in the first 11 months this year while its imports
went down by 33.3 percent compared with the same period of last
year, the newspaper Politika reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Exports totaled 1.3 billion U.S. dollars while imports dropped
to 2.9 billion dollars in the period, as a result of the 78-day
airstrikes by the U.S.-led NATO earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
Exports and imports in November went down by 16.1 and 55.5
percent from October respectively.
</P>
<P>
Italy, Germany, Macedonia and Russia are at present
Yugoslavia's major trading partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
