<HEADLINE> Italian Central Bank Chief Calls on Government to Lower Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Italy Governor Antonio
Fazio called on the government to bring down the level of taxation
on Monday, arguing that lower taxes would boost the country's
flagging economy.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the finance police training academy in the
Italian northern city of Bergamo, Fazio said that "while
respecting international commitments to reduce the level of our
public debt, it is necessary to move more firmly towards a steady
reduction in fiscal pressure."
</P>
<P>
"We must implement the measures outlined in the budget with
plans for further reductions over the following years," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that lower taxes would stimulate economic growth as
they would "give hope to numerous young people entering the job
market."
</P>
<P>
"The loss of competitiveness is reflected in a reduction of
foreign trade activity. Jobs become concentrated in economically
advanced regions and increasingly take the form of short-term
contracts."
</P>
<P>
He said that structural reforms are necessary and would make
Italy more competitive.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government was swift in responding to Fazio's
remarks: Finance Minister Vicenzo Visco told reporters that the
government had been pursuing a policy of lower taxes for the last
four years.
</P>
<P>
"There has already been a partial reduction in fiscal pressure
and we will stick to this path," Visco said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
