<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Senior Citizens Turn to Community Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Although Chinese children
traditionally take care of their elderly parents, more and more
senior citizens say they will turn to community services for the
help their kids don't have time to give.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey by the Population and Development
Research Institute at the Tianjin-based Nankai University, most
younger family members think that caring for their elderly parents
will interfere with their job -- even though they are willing to
do so.
</P>
<P>
Most senior citizens, according to the survey, don't want to be
a burden to their children, while the rest still hope the kids can
lend a hand with the routine needs, such as providing medical care
and entertainment, food shopping, and doing the laundry.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted in Beijing and Tianjin, showed that about
54 percent of the elderly like to use the low-cost services
provided by communities or local residents' committees.
</P>
<P>
About 22 percent of them, however, turned down community
assistance because they feared they wouldn't get good service or
it would be too expensive.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin, a port city in north China, has about 1.2 million
people over age 60, which is 13.15 percent of the total population
of the city. By early 1998, about ten percent of the total 1.2
billion Chinese people were over 60, and the number is growing by
three percent annually.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government, enterprises and individual investors
have spent a large sum of money to provide high-quality community
services for the senior citizens. So far, more than 100 apartment
buildings have been set up for the elderly in Tianjin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
