<HEADLINE> Mexico, Spain Modify Extradition Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Mexico
and Spain signed here on Monday the second protocol modifying the
existing Treaty of Extradition and Mutual Assistance in Penal
Matters.
</P>
<P>
The document, signed by Mexican Attorney General Jorge Madrazo
and Spain's Justice Minister Margarita Mariscal de Gante Miron,
shows the two countries' desire to strengthen cooperation on the
fight against crimes, the Federal Attorney General's Office (PGR)
said in a communique.
</P>
<P>
Mexico and Spain have kept in force the Treaty of Extradition
and Mutual Assistance in Penal Matters since June 1, 1980. The
first modifying was signed on June 23, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The PGR said the Spanish official was on a three-day visit to
Mexico during which he would also have a meeting with the
president of the Supreme Court of Justice of Mexico, David Gongora.
</P>
