<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Attorney General Reopens Soeharto's Corruption Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Attorney General
's Office has said it was reopening the investigation into alleged
corruption by former president Soeharto, national newspapers
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Based on the investigation by the Attorney General's Office,
we have found new aspects (enabling) the reopening of the
investigation against Soeharto," Attorney General Marzuki Darusman
said in a written statement published by the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki said evidence pointed to "a misuse of power and
authority"in issuing government regulations and presidential
decrees to amass funds for foundations linked to Soeharto, his
family and associates.
</P>
<P>
"Soeharto as a president, who had the authority to issue
government and presidential decrees, is suspected of misusing his
authority as a means to collect money to finance the foundations
he chaired, and for the benefit of his family and cronies ...
which directly and indirectly caused state losses," he said.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki said his office was revoking a letter issued by then
attorney general Ismudjoko on October 11 suspending the
investigation into Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, who was forced down in May last year, is accused of
massive corrupt, collusive and nepotistic practices during his 32
years in power.
</P>
<P>
However, the Attorney General's Office, after months of
investigation, found no evidence of wrongdoing by Soeharto and the
investigation was halted on October 11 during the last week of B.J.
Habibie's presidency.
</P>
<P>
Since being sworn in as attorney general in October, Marzuki
has expressed his commitment to reopening the investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
