<HEADLINE> Britain's New Ambassador to Libya Seeks Fresh Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new ambassador to
Libya on Monday promised to "make a fresh start" to the relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Richard Dalton, who was appointed as Britain's ambassador to
Tripoli after the two countries ended their 15 year political
impasse, said he wanted to help Tripoli return to the "mainstream
of the international community."
</P>
<P>
"We're making this fresh start. We will be proceeding
cautiously," Dalton said at the Foreign Office in London.
</P>
<P>
"We want the relationship to be on a sound and stable basis,"
said Dalton.
</P>
<P>
He said the groundwork for the resumption of ties with Libyan
leader Muammar Gaddafi had been laid in talks before a July
declaration that Libya would cooperate with investigations into
the fatal shooting in 1984 of British policewoman Yvonne Fletcher
outside Libya's embassy in London.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said last month Libya had agreed
to pay compensation to Fletcher's family and the money, reported
by British newspapers to be 250,000 pounds ($404,900), had been
handed over.
</P>
<P>
Libya had also agreed to support international efforts in
fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In April, the two suspects wanted by the United states and
Britain for the bombing in 1988 of a Pan-Am airliner, over the
Scottish town of Lockerbie, which killed 270 people were handed to
a Scottish court sitting in a hired military camp in Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The two will be tried next February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
