<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes U.N. Vote on Iraq This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Monday that five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council
had made "a good deal of progress" on a new arms inspection regime
for Iraq and a U.N. vote would probably take place this week.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that a Security Council vote on the omnibus draft
is likely this week," State Department spokesman James Foley told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The five countries -- Britain, China, France, Russia and the
United States -- have been negotiating for months over the terms
they should set for an end to the trade sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The draft U.N. resolution links suspending the sanctions with
Iraq accepting the new inspection system, to replace the UNSCOM
system which broke down last year after the U.S. and British
barbarous bombing of the country.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see this draft adopted with the broadest
possible support among council members," Foley said. "I can't
predict an exact time for the vote or indeed what the vote count
will be but there is an increasing view that the time has come to
vote and to resolve this matter clearly."
</P>
<P>
Foley said the United States hoped for progress on the
resolution by Saturday of this week, when the latest U.N. oil-for-
food program for Iraq runs out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
