<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian FM Urges End to Reprisals Against Serbs in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini warned Monday that reports arriving from Kosovo suggest that
the Albanian Kosovars are pursuing something like ethnic cleansing
against the province's Serb and other minorities.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency Ansa, Dini, who is now present
at the European union (EU) Foreign Ministers meeting in Brussels,
said that "the reports we are receiving go in that direction could
almost say the international community has proven incapable of
ending violence against minorities in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, NATO waged an air war on Yugoslavia with the
declared international aim of halting Serbian ethnic cleansing
against the Albanian Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
Since Serbian forces withdrew from the province, there has been
a rising number of reports of Albanian attacks on members of the
Serb, Croatian and Rom minorities.
</P>
<P>
"The Croatians were chased out of a village where they had
lived for 700 years," said Dini, warning that the international
community's commitment to defending the Albanians must be matched
by a similar commitment to the other ethnic groups in the province.
</P>
<P>
Dini added that the head of the civilian administration set up
in Kosovo by the U.N., Bernard Kouchmer, was complaining that he
has neither the forces nor the means to prevent violence and
reprisal in the province.
</P>
<P>
Dini also had harsh words for the KLA, the ex-Kosovar
liberation army, which he said should be issued with a "strong
call" to respect U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
In particular, he charged that the KLA is illegally levying
taxes on the Kosovars to run a "government-style" administration
in parallel with the UN's.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he pointed out, the KLA asks the EU and the
international community to pay the wages of Kosovars employed by
some parts of the province's administration.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is unthinkable that people should not be aware of
how the KLA behaves," said Dini. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for More Attention to HIV/AIDS in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Monday called for more efforts to sped up the work on
developing a vaccine, to use every possible means to halt the
spread of the diseases in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief, in his speech to the meeting on International
Partnerships Against HIV/AIDS in Africa, painted a gloomy picture
on the serious problem of AIDS in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the international community should work hard "to
break the conspiracy of silence at every level," "to meet the
needs of those already infected and their families," and "to make
effective treatment available, at a price African societies can
afford," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Twenty years ago, the global community had not even heard of
AIDS," he said. "Today, the AIDS pandemic -- unexpected,
unexplained, unspeakably cruel -- presents us, especially in
Africa, with a tragedy we can barely comprehend, let alone manage.
"
</P>
<P>
"Africa's southern and eastern region, with less than five
percent of the world's population, is home to more than 50 percent
to those living with HIV," the virus that can cause the AIDS
disease, he said. "It is where 60 percent of all AIDS deaths have
happened so far."
</P>
<P>
"And it is where a whole generation of children is now losing
its parents to AIDS," he said. "By the end of this year, the
global epidemic will have left 11 million orphans -- and 90
percent of them will be African children."
</P>
<P>
All this is an unbearable tragedy and burden for millions of
individuals and their families, he said, adding that it is also
devastating the economies of their countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is taking away both breadwinners and those who look after
the young, the old, and the infirm," he said. "It is destroying
the very fabric of society."
</P>
<P>
"AIDS leaves poor countries poorer still, and thus even more
vulnerable to infection," he said. "It brings in its wake
discrimination, prejudice, and often violations of human rights.
It is taking away not only Africa's present, but also its future."
</P>
<P>
"This unprecedented crisis requires an unprecedented response --
a response from all of us, whoever and wherever we are," he said.
"A response that makes humanity live up to its name."
</P>
<P>
"Our response so far has failed Africa," he said. "From now on,
let us resolve that failure is not an option."
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, held at the U.N. headquarters in New York,
is designed to form an international partnership against HIV/AIDS
in Africa by calling for a response to the killing epidemic in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The meeting attracted representatives from Africa and the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD)
Governments, U.N. agencies, civil society and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
It is intended to be the start of a process to launch a five-
year initiative to reduce HIV infections, particularly among 15-to-
24-year olds in the most affected countries.
</P>
<P>
"The actual launch of the International Partnership against
AIDS in Africa is expected next spring," a U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0316 </DOCNO>
