<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West Ham Play to Goalless Draw with Spurs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Shaka Hislop became the hero of
West Ham United this evening with two brilliant saves which earned
the team a hard-earned goalless draw at Tottenham Hotspur at
English premier league.
</P>
<P>
The West Ham goalkeeper denied Spurs full points after his team
had to play the entire second half without captain Steve Lomas,
who was dismissed moments before the interval.
</P>
<P>
Lomas was sent off after his second yellow card offense for a
wild kick. The midfielder had collected his first caution when a
linesman flagged for an off-the-ball incident.
</P>
<P>
He was the only player to be dismissed in the weekend's 10
premier league games.
</P>
<P>
It was the solitary notable incident of a first period in which
both goalkeepers were largely unemployed -- hardly unexpected
considering both sides went into the game separated by only two
places and two points.
</P>
<P>
David Ginola and Jose Dominguez tried hard to create chances
for Spurs but while their work rates were commendable, their snap
shots were wildly off target and their crosses easily dealt with
by West Ham's defense.
</P>
<P>
Steffen Iversen had a great chance to break the deadlock for
Tottenham in the 51st minute when Ginola found him just outside
the goalmouth. But the Norwegian's effort went narrowly wide.
</P>
<P>
In the 76th minute, Hislop somehow tipped away a fierce goal-
bound shot from close range by Chris Perry.
</P>
<P>
With only three minutes left, Hislop made his best save of the
match, tipping Chris Armstrong's powerful header on to the bar.
Iversen's volley from the rebound just missed the net.
</P>
<P>
West Ham, unbeaten in their last three league games, had their
moments too, particularly when Marc Vivien Foe mis-timed his
attempt from inside the goalmouth in the 70th minute and the ball
cannoned away off the legs of Tottenham goalkeeper Ian Walker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
