<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Aircraft Maintenance Company Guilty in Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. aircraft maintenance
company was found guilty Monday in a 1996 plane crash that killed
all 110 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
A court in Miami convicted SabreTech of improperly packaging
the oxygen canisters blamed for the cargo hold fire that caused
the ValuJet crash in the Everglades, Florida.
</P>
<P>
The company was convicted of eight counts of causing the air
transportation of hazardous materials and one count of failing to
provide training in handling hazardous materials.
</P>
<P>
Two former employees of the company were acquitted of
conspiracy and charges they lied on repair records.
</P>
<P>
SabreTech could face 2.25 million dollars fines and be forced
to make restitution to the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
The case involved 144 oxygen generators removed by SabreTech
from other ValuJet planes and delivered to the ill-fated flight
without the required safety caps or any markings indicating the
canisters were hazardous.
</P>
<P>
The federal case marked the first time that a maintenance
company faced criminal charges in connection with an American air
disaster.
</P>
<P>
SabreTech lawyer Ken Quinn said the guilty verdicts would be
appealed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
