<DOCNO> XIE19991207.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Fined Over Unauthorized Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Nottingham Forest have pleaded
guilty before a Football Association commission to a misconduct
charge relating to unauthorized payments to management and playing
staff.
</P>
<P>
The commission ordered that the club be censured, ordered to
pay the costs of the hearing and fined 25,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
Payments were made to staff outside of their contracts with
Forest covering a period from 1984 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
The charge resulted from evidence passed to the FA following
the FA Premier League inquiry into allegations of irregular
payments.
</P>
<P>
At the hearing in Nottingham the commission heard that a series
of cash payments in the region of 150-500 pounds were made by the
club to management staff.
</P>
<P>
Unauthorized bonus payments were also offered to players as an
inducement to win matches during a period from 1988 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
The payments were not recorded in the players' contracts, in
breach of FA rules.
</P>
<P>
The FA accepted that the current management and administration
of Nottingham Forest played no part in the activities which
resulted in the breach of rules.
</P>
<P>
It was also accepted that, in particular given the club's
status as a subsidiary of a public limited company, Forest now
have improved financial controls in place to prevent any
recurrence.
</P>
<P>
The commission took into account the size of the payments and
that no irregular payments have been made since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
